{"title_page": "Dasharatha", "text_new": "{{About|character from Hindu Epic Ramayana|Maurya King|Dasharatha Maurya}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{More references|date=April 2016}}'''''Dasharatha''''' was a descendant of the [[Raghuvanshi]]-[[Ikshvaku dynasty|Ikshvaku]]-[[Suryavansha]] dynasty and the [[Maharaja]] of [[Ayodhya]] as mentioned in the Hindu epic, the [[Ramayana]].\n\nDasharatha was the son of [[Aja of Kosala|Aja]] and Indumati. He had three wives; [[Kausalya]], [[Kaikeyi]] and [[Sumitra|blablablaSumitra]] and out of the union born [[Rama]] (the principal character in the Ramayana), [[Bharata (Ramayana)|Bharata]], [[Lakshmana]] and [[Shatrughna]].\nKing Dasharatha was incarnation of Dronavasu Brahmin, who received a boon from Lord Vishnu in his first life in Satyayuga.\n\n==Early life==\n\nDasharatha was the son of King Aja of Ayodhya and Princess Indumati of [[Vidarbha]]. His birth name was Nemi, but he acquired the name Dasharatha as his chariot could move in all ten directions, fly as well as come down on earth and he could fight with ease in all these directions.\n\nDasharatha became the King after his parents died. He was a great warrior who single-handedly conquered the whole earth with his prowess and defeated and slew many Asuras in war.\n\nDasharath had three queen consorts, namely, [[Kaushalya]], [[Sumitra]] and [[Kaikeyi]]. Kaushalya was from the Kingdom of [[Magadha]]. Sumitra was from [[Varanasi|Kashi]]. Kaikeyi was from [[Kekeya Kingdom]]. Having an immense desire to beget a son, Dasharath promised Kaikeyi that the son she bore would succeed him as King of Ayodhya after she pleaded with him in the Kop Bhavan.\n\n==Yaj\u00f1a to beget sons==\n[[File:Dasharatha give Payasa to his wives.jpg|thumb|250px|Dasharatha gives Payasa to his wives]]\n\nDasharath performed a [[yaj\u00f1a]] with the help of Sage [[Rishyasringa]] on the advice of [[Vasishtha]].\n\nThe [[Yaj\u00f1a]] was the Putra-kameshti at the bank of Manorama river. Dasharath and Kaushalya had a daughter [[Shanta]], who was Rishyashringa's wife. As the conclusion of the [[Yagna]] drew near, [[Agni]] sprang out from the Yagnakunda (sacrificial fire pit) and handed Dasharatha a pot of [[kheer]] ([[payasa]]), advising him to distribute it among his queens.\n\nKaushalya ate half the kheer, Sumitra ate a quarter of it. Kaikeyi ate some and passed the pot back to Sumitra who consumed the kheer for the second time.\n\nThus the princes were conceived after the consumption of the kheer. Since Kaushalya had consumed the largest portion she gave birth to [[Rama]]. Kaikeyi gave birth to [[Bharata (Ramayana)|Bharata]]. Sumitra, who had consumed the kheer twice, gave birth to [[Lakshmana]] and [[Shatrughna]].\n\n==Killing of Shravan Kumara==\n{{unsourced section|date=November 2019}}\nAfter Rama's departure to the forest, Dasharatha lies in his bed with a wailing Kaushalya. He suddenly remembers an incident which had occurred in the past. He narrates to Kaushalya about how, by accident, he had killed a young boy named [[Shravan|Shravana]] mistaking him to be an elephant. Dasharatha who was then a crown prince had gone hunting on the banks of River Saryu. He was an expert in hunting by determining the direction of sound and heard the gurgle of an animal drinking water. Mistaking it to be water flowing through the trunk of an elephant, Dasharatha shot an arrow. He became mortified when he heard a human cry as the arrow found its target. Dasharatha hurried there to find a boy lying sprawled on the banks of the river with an arrow lodged in his chest. The boy forgives Dasharatha for his unintentional unrighteous act and demands that he pull the arrow out of his chest. He also tells him to take the pitcher of water to his blind parents who must be waiting for him. The boy dies. Dasharatha approaches the blind couple and tells them about their son's unfortunate death. The parents, grief-stricken curse the prince: \"Just as we are dying due to the separation from our beloved son, you too shall have the same fate.\" Dasharatha concludes the chapter by saying that his end is near and the curse has taken effect. The place where Dasharatha killed [[Shravan|Shravana]] is now known as [[Shravan Kshetra]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/and-more/lord-rama-s-father-king-dasharatha-was-cursed-by-an-old-couple-here-s-why_1948399.html|title=Lord Rama\u2019s father King Dasharatha was cursed by an old couple- Here\u2019s why|last=|first=|date=2016-11-10|website=Zee News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Demise==\n\nFollowing his narration of Shravana, Dasharatha dies in the night due to the pain and misery of his separation from Rama. His funeral rites were performed by [[Bharata (Ramayana)|Bharata]] and [[Shatrughna]] who were called back from Kekeya.\n[[File:Bharata fainted during his father Dasratha's cremation.jpg|thumb|left|Bharata fainted during his father Dasratha's cremation.]]\nHis Palace is in Ayodhya district (U.P.) about 18.1&nbsp;km away from Bilhar Ghat. It is beside the bank of the [[Sarayu]] River where he was cremated. This place is very devotional for Hindus.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://www.google.co.in/maps/dir/Bilhar+Ghat,+Kandipur,+Uttar+Pradesh+224161/Ayodhya/@26.7359802,82.1961675,13z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m13!4m12!1m5!1m1!1s0x3990a6d2a0b8916f:0xf14b0e4b2011b6ef!2m2!1d82.2692779!2d26.6815868!1m5!1m1!1s0x399a07937e6d2823:0x5fc8f683b17f222b!2m2!1d82.1985518!2d26.7879633/ Distance from Ayodhya City to Bilhar Ghat]\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Dasharatha}}\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/24869 Ramayana, translated in English by] [[Ralph T. H. Griffith|Griffith]], from [[Project Gutenberg]]\n* [http://www.valmikiramayana.net/etext/Valmiki Ramayana by] [[Valmiki]]\n* [http://www.astrojyoti.com/ramacharitamanasindex.htm/etext/Tulsidas Ramayana by]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} [[Tulsidas]]\n\n{{Ramayana}}\n\n[[Category:Raghuvamsa]]\n[[Category:Ayodhya]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|character from Hindu Epic Ramayana|Maurya King|Dasharatha Maurya}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{More references|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n|name=Dasharatha\n| title              = [[Maharaja]] of [[Kosala]]\n|birth_name=\n|birth_place=[[Ayodhya]], [[Kosala]] (present-day [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]])\n|death_place=Ayodhya, Kosala (present-day Uttar Pradesh, India)\n|image=King Dasharatha grieves inconsolably at his obligation to banish Rama to the forest.jpg\n|caption = King Dasharatha grieves inconsolably at his obligation to banish Rama to the forest\n|succession=[[Maharaja]] of [[Kosala]]\n|successor=[[Rama]]\n|predecessor = [[Aja of Kosala|Aja]]\n|dynasty =[[Raghuvanshi]]-[[Ikshvaku dynasty|Ikshvaku]]-[[Suryavansha|Suryavanshi]]\n|religion=[[Hinduism]]\n|spouse-type=Consort(s)\n|spouse=[[Kausalya]] <br> [[Sumitra]] <br> [[Kaikeyi]]\n|issue = [[Rama]] <br> [[Bharata(Ramayana)|Bharatha]] <br> [[Lakshmana]] <br> [[Shatrughna]] <br> [[Shanta]]\n|father=Aja\n|mother=Indumati\n}}\n\n'''''Dasharatha''''' was a descendant of the [[Raghuvanshi]]-[[Ikshvaku dynasty|Ikshvaku]]-[[Suryavansha]] dynasty and the [[Maharaja]] of [[Ayodhya]] as mentioned in the Hindu epic, the [[Ramayana]].\n\nDasharatha was the son of [[Aja of Kosala|Aja]] and Indumati. He had three wives; [[Kausalya]], [[Kaikeyi]] and [[Sumitra]] and out of the union born [[Rama]] (the principal character in the Ramayana), [[Bharata (Ramayana)|Bharata]], [[Lakshmana]] and [[Shatrughna]].\nKing Dasharatha was incarnation of Dronavasu Brahmin, who received a boon from Lord Vishnu in his first life in Satyayuga.\n\n==Early life==\n\nDasharatha was the son of King Aja of Ayodhya and Princess Indumati of [[Vidarbha]]. His birth name was Nemi, but he acquired the name Dasharatha as his chariot could move in all ten directions, fly as well as come down on earth and he could fight with ease in all these directions.\n\nDasharatha became the King after his parents died. He was a great warrior who single-handedly conquered the whole earth with his prowess and defeated and slew many Asuras in war.\n\nDasharath had three queen consorts, namely, [[Kaushalya]], [[Sumitra]] and [[Kaikeyi]]. Kaushalya was from the Kingdom of [[Magadha]]. Sumitra was from [[Varanasi|Kashi]]. Kaikeyi was from [[Kekeya Kingdom]]. Having an immense desire to beget a son, Dasharath promised Kaikeyi that the son she bore would succeed him as King of Ayodhya after she pleaded with him in the Kop Bhavan.\n\n==Yaj\u00f1a to beget sons==\n[[File:Dasharatha give Payasa to his wives.jpg|thumb|250px|Dasharatha gives Payasa to his wives]]\n\nDasharath performed a [[yaj\u00f1a]] with the help of Sage [[Rishyasringa]] on the advice of [[Vasishtha]].\n\nThe [[Yaj\u00f1a]] was the Putra-kameshti at the bank of Manorama river. Dasharath and Kaushalya had a daughter [[Shanta]], who was Rishyashringa's wife. As the conclusion of the [[Yagna]] drew near, [[Agni]] sprang out from the Yagnakunda (sacrificial fire pit) and handed Dasharatha a pot of [[kheer]] ([[payasa]]), advising him to distribute it among his queens.\n\nKaushalya ate half the kheer, Sumitra ate a quarter of it. Kaikeyi ate some and passed the pot back to Sumitra who consumed the kheer for the second time.\n\nThus the princes were conceived after the consumption of the kheer. Since Kaushalya had consumed the largest portion she gave birth to [[Rama]]. Kaikeyi gave birth to [[Bharata (Ramayana)|Bharata]]. Sumitra, who had consumed the kheer twice, gave birth to [[Lakshmana]] and [[Shatrughna]].\n\n==Killing of Shravan Kumara==\n{{unsourced section|date=November 2019}}\nAfter Rama's departure to the forest, Dasharatha lies in his bed with a wailing Kaushalya. He suddenly remembers an incident which had occurred in the past. He narrates to Kaushalya about how, by accident, he had killed a young boy named [[Shravan|Shravana]] mistaking him to be an elephant. Dasharatha who was then a crown prince had gone hunting on the banks of River Saryu. He was an expert in hunting by determining the direction of sound and heard the gurgle of an animal drinking water. Mistaking it to be water flowing through the trunk of an elephant, Dasharatha shot an arrow. He became mortified when he heard a human cry as the arrow found its target. Dasharatha hurried there to find a boy lying sprawled on the banks of the river with an arrow lodged in his chest. The boy forgives Dasharatha for his unintentional unrighteous act and demands that he pull the arrow out of his chest. He also tells him to take the pitcher of water to his blind parents who must be waiting for him. The boy dies. Dasharatha approaches the blind couple and tells them about their son's unfortunate death. The parents, grief-stricken curse the prince: \"Just as we are dying due to the separation from our beloved son, you too shall have the same fate.\" Dasharatha concludes the chapter by saying that his end is near and the curse has taken effect. The place where Dasharatha killed [[Shravan|Shravana]] is now known as [[Shravan Kshetra]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/and-more/lord-rama-s-father-king-dasharatha-was-cursed-by-an-old-couple-here-s-why_1948399.html|title=Lord Rama\u2019s father King Dasharatha was cursed by an old couple- Here\u2019s why|last=|first=|date=2016-11-10|website=Zee News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Demise==\n\nFollowing his narration of Shravana, Dasharatha dies in the night due to the pain and misery of his separation from Rama. His funeral rites were performed by [[Bharata (Ramayana)|Bharata]] and [[Shatrughna]] who were called back from Kekeya.\n[[File:Bharata fainted during his father Dasratha's cremation.jpg|thumb|left|Bharata fainted during his father Dasratha's cremation.]]\nHis Palace is in Ayodhya district (U.P.) about 18.1&nbsp;km away from Bilhar Ghat. It is beside the bank of the [[Sarayu]] River where he was cremated. This place is very devotional for Hindus.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://www.google.co.in/maps/dir/Bilhar+Ghat,+Kandipur,+Uttar+Pradesh+224161/Ayodhya/@26.7359802,82.1961675,13z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m13!4m12!1m5!1m1!1s0x3990a6d2a0b8916f:0xf14b0e4b2011b6ef!2m2!1d82.2692779!2d26.6815868!1m5!1m1!1s0x399a07937e6d2823:0x5fc8f683b17f222b!2m2!1d82.1985518!2d26.7879633/ Distance from Ayodhya City to Bilhar Ghat]\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Dasharatha}}\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/24869 Ramayana, translated in English by] [[Ralph T. H. Griffith|Griffith]], from [[Project Gutenberg]]\n* [http://www.valmikiramayana.net/etext/Valmiki Ramayana by] [[Valmiki]]\n* [http://www.astrojyoti.com/ramacharitamanasindex.htm/etext/Tulsidas Ramayana by]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} [[Tulsidas]]\n\n{{Ramayana}}\n\n[[Category:Raghuvamsa]]\n[[Category:Ayodhya]]\n", "name_user": "116.72.50.168", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(G)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dasharatha"}
{"title_page": "Craig Bernard", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian film Director}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Craig Bernard\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]] -->\n| birth_place      = Canada<!--\n-->{{Infobox|child=yes\n| label1 = Alma mater\n| data1  = [[University of Toronto]]}}\n| genre            = [[Music video]]s\n| occupation       = [[Executive Producer]], [[Film director|director]]<!--\n-->{{Infobox|child=yes\n| label1 = Organizations\n| data1  = BLVD Industries, Refused TV, Blink Pictures, Fever Content}}\n| years_active     = 2001\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} or {{Official URL}} -->\n}}\n'''Craig Bernard'''  is a Canadian film director and executive producer. He is best known for his music videos for musical groups such as [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]], [[Stone Sour]], [[Avicii]], [[Bruno Mars]], and [[Grouplove]], along with his work in the VR space.\n\n== Career ==\nBernard studied English at the [[University of Toronto]], then worked as a concert photographer in Vancouver.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://showbizbytes.com/bruno-mars-aviici-john-newman-an-interview-with-music-video-director-craig-bernard-39727b735866|title=Bruno Mars, Aviici, John Newman: An Interview With Music Video Director Craig Bernard|last=Vivien|first=Ralph|date=Aug 11, 2017|website=Showbiz Bytes}}</ref> After becoming involved with production and writing treatments for several productions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://six-questions.com/craig-bernard-spreading-the-fever-of-vr-content-660a9d2c82d4|title=Craig Bernard: Spreading the Fever of VR Content|last=Tobogan|first=Randy|website=Six Questions}}</ref> he directed his first music video in 2001 for the Canadian band [[Jersey (band)|Jersey]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvdbase.com/person.php?id=C3569|title=Craig Bernard|website=MVDBase}}</ref> In 2003, Bernard received two separate nominations for The [[Juno Award]]\u2019s Video of The Year, for his videos for [[David Usher]]\u2019s \u201c[[Black Black Heart]]\u201d and [[Danko Jones]]\u2019 \u201cLovercall\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://junoawards.ca/artist-profiles/craig-bernard/|title=Artist Profile: Craig Bernard|website=Juno Awards}}</ref> Most recently, Bernard directed the music video for [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]]\u2019s \u201c[[The Light (Disturbed song)|The Light]]\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/disturbed-taps-directors-culley-bunker-and-craig-bernard-for-the-light-video/|title=DISTURBED Taps Directors CULLEY BUNKER And CRAIG BERNARD For 'The Light' Video|date=October 12, 2015|website=Blabbermouth}}</ref>\n\nBernard later transitioned from VFX-heavy music videos to the VR space<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.currentartisan.com/craig-bernard-interview/|title=Does A Rising Tide Lift All Boats? A Conversation with Producer Craig Bernard on The Future of VR|date=2019-09-23|website=Current Artisan|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref> first became involved with VR content through his work as an Executive Producer on the project Dark Ride,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theinspirationroom.com/daily/2010/lexus-dark-ride/|title=Dark Ride|last=McLeod|first=Duncan|date=May 17, 2010|website=Inspiration Room}}</ref> a 360 branded content created for [[Lexus]]. He subsequently began working with the production company SAMO VR, producing the 2016 [[Eden (musician)|Eden]] VR music video \u201cDrugs\u201d.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/elia-petridis-launches-virtual-reality-company-fever-content-exclusive/|title=Elia Petridis Launches Virtual Reality Company: Fever Content (Exclusive)|last=Pressberg|first=Matt|date=July 5, 2017|website=The Wrap}}</ref> In 2017, Bernard became the Executive Producer at Fever Content, a Los Angeles-based Immersive Entertainment company,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://virtualrealitypop.com/as-demand-for-vr-content-picks-up-a-host-of-exciting-new-companies-have-formed-to-answer-the-call-50ca0aaa8fd6|title=As Demand for VR Content Picks Up, New Companies Formed To Answer Call|website=Virtual Reality Pop}}</ref> however, in a 2019 interview he revealed that he had stepped down from his role in the company to focus on other projects<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.currentartisan.com/craig-bernard-interview/|title=Does A Rising Tide Lift All Boats? A Conversation with Producer Craig Bernard on The Future of VR|date=2019-09-23|website=Current Artisan|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n==== Director ====\n* [[High Holy Days (band)|High Holy Days]] \"[[All My Real Friends]]\" (2004)<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|title=@ mvdbase.com|url=http://mvdbase.com/person.php?id=C3569|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n* [[Danko Jones|Dank Jones]] \"[[I Want Your Sex|I Want You]]\" (2003)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* [[Theory of a Deadman]] \"[[Theory of a Deadman (album)|Point to Prove]]\" (2003)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* [[Treble Charger]] \"[[Dont believe it all|Don't Believe It Al]]<nowiki/>l\" (2002)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* [[Jersey (band)|Jersey]] \"Saturday Night\" (2001)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* [[David Usher]] \"[[Black Black Heart]]\" (2001)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* [[Danko Jones|Dank Jones]] \"Lovercall\" (2001)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Executive Producer ====\n\n* [[Eden (musician)|Eden]] \"Drugs\" (2016)\n* [[Wolf Alice]] \"[[You're a Germ|You're A Germ]]\" (2015)<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm3436820/|title=Craig Bernard|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n* [[Kaskade]] \"Never Sleep Alone\" (2015)<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://imvdb.com/n/craig-bernard|title=Craig Bernard|website=IMVDb|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n* [[Grouplove]] \"I'm With You\" (2014)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Chromeo]] \"Come Alive\" (2014)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Avicii]] \"[[Hey Brother]]\" (2013)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Grouplove]] \"Ways to Go\" (2013)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Colbie Caillat]] \"Hold On\" (2013)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Grouplove]] \"Shark Attack\" (2013)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Bruno Mars]] \"[[Locked Out of Heaven]]\" (2012)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Kerli]] \"[[The Lucky Ones (song)|The Lucky Ones]]\" (2012)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Bruno Mars]] \"[[When I Was Your Man]]\" (2012)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Twin Atlantic]] \"What is Light? Where is Laughter?\" (2011)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[CeeLo Green|Ceelo Green]] \"[[I Want You (Cee-Lo Green song)|I want You]]\" (2011)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Inna]] \"[[Club Rocker]]\" (2011)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Awolnation]] \"[[Kill Your Heroes]]\" (2011)<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[imdbname:3436820|Craig Bernard on IMDb]]\n* [https://imvdb.com/n/craig-bernard Craig Bernard on IMVMDb]\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.mvdbase.com/person.php?id=C3569|title=Craig Bernard|website=Music Video DataBase|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912055824/http://www.mvdbase.com/person.php?id=C3569|archivedate=12 September 2017|url-status=live}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bernard, Craig}}\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian film producers]]\n[[Category:American music video directors]]\n[[Category:American music video producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian music video directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Music video producers]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian film Director}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Craig Bernard\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]] -->\n| birth_place      = Canada<!--\n-->{{Infobox|child=yes\n| label1 = Alma mater\n| data1  = [[University of Toronto]]}}\n| genre            = [[Music video]]s\n| occupation       = [[Executive Producer]], [[Film director|director]]<!--\n-->{{Infobox|child=yes\n| label1 = Organizations\n| data1  = BLVD Industries, Refused TV, Blink Pictures, Fever Content}}\n| years_active     = 2001\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} or {{Official URL}} -->\n}}\n'''Craig Bernard'''  is a Canadian film Director and executive producer. He is best known for his music videos for musical groups such as [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]], [[Stone Sour]], [[Avicii]], [[Bruno Mars]], and [[Grouplove]], along with his work in the VR space.\n\n== Career ==\nBernard studied English at the University of Toronto, then worked as a concert photographer in Vancouver.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://showbizbytes.com/bruno-mars-aviici-john-newman-an-interview-with-music-video-director-craig-bernard-39727b735866|title=Bruno Mars, Aviici, John Newman: An Interview With Music Video Director Craig Bernard|last=Vivien|first=Ralph|date=Aug 11, 2017|website=Showbiz Bytes}}</ref> After becoming involved with production and writing treatments for several productions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://six-questions.com/craig-bernard-spreading-the-fever-of-vr-content-660a9d2c82d4|title=Craig Bernard: Spreading the Fever of VR Content|last=Tobogan|first=Randy|website=Six Questions}}</ref> he directed his first music video in 2001 for the Canadian band [[Jersey (band)|Jersey]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvdbase.com/person.php?id=C3569|title=Craig Bernard|website=MVDBase}}</ref> In 2003, Bernard received two separate nominations for The [[Juno Award]]\u2019s Video of The Year, for his videos for [[David Usher]]\u2019s \u201c[[Black Black Heart]]\u201d and [[Danko Jones]]\u2019 \u201cLovercall\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://junoawards.ca/artist-profiles/craig-bernard/|title=Artist Profile: Craig Bernard|website=Juno Awards}}</ref> Most recently, Bernard directed the music video for [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]]\u2019s \u201c[[The Light (Disturbed song)|The Light]]\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/disturbed-taps-directors-culley-bunker-and-craig-bernard-for-the-light-video/|title=DISTURBED Taps Directors CULLEY BUNKER And CRAIG BERNARD For 'The Light' Video|date=October 12, 2015|website=Blabbermouth}}</ref>\n\nBernard later transitioned from VFX-heavy music videos to the VR space<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.currentartisan.com/craig-bernard-interview/|title=Does A Rising Tide Lift All Boats? A Conversation with Producer Craig Bernard on The Future of VR|date=2019-09-23|website=Current Artisan|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref> first became involved with VR content through his work as an Executive Producer on the project Dark Ride,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theinspirationroom.com/daily/2010/lexus-dark-ride/|title=Dark Ride|last=McLeod|first=Duncan|date=May 17, 2010|website=Inspiration Room}}</ref> a 360 branded content created for [[Lexus]]. He subsequently began working with the production company SAMO VR, producing the 2016 [[Eden (musician)|Eden]] VR music video \u201cDrugs\u201d.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/elia-petridis-launches-virtual-reality-company-fever-content-exclusive/|title=Elia Petridis Launches Virtual Reality Company: Fever Content (Exclusive)|last=Pressberg|first=Matt|date=July 5, 2017|website=The Wrap}}</ref> In 2017, Bernard became the Executive Producer at Fever Content, a Los Angeles-based Immersive Entertainment company,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://virtualrealitypop.com/as-demand-for-vr-content-picks-up-a-host-of-exciting-new-companies-have-formed-to-answer-the-call-50ca0aaa8fd6|title=As Demand for VR Content Picks Up, New Companies Formed To Answer Call|website=Virtual Reality Pop}}</ref> however, in a 2019 interview he revealed that he had stepped down from his role in the company to focus on other projects<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.currentartisan.com/craig-bernard-interview/|title=Does A Rising Tide Lift All Boats? A Conversation with Producer Craig Bernard on The Future of VR|date=2019-09-23|website=Current Artisan|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n==== Director ====\n* [[High Holy Days (band)|High Holy Days]] \"[[All My Real Friends]]\" (2004)<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|title=@ mvdbase.com|url=http://mvdbase.com/person.php?id=C3569|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n* [[Danko Jones|Dank Jones]] \"[[I Want Your Sex|I Want You]]\" (2003)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* [[Theory of a Deadman]] \"[[Theory of a Deadman (album)|Point to Prove]]\" (2003)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* [[Treble Charger]] \"[[Dont believe it all|Don't Believe It Al]]<nowiki/>l\" (2002)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* [[Jersey (band)|Jersey]] \"Saturday Night\" (2001)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* [[David Usher]] \"[[Black Black Heart]]\" (2001)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* [[Danko Jones|Dank Jones]] \"Lovercall\" (2001)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Executive Producer ====\n\n* [[Eden (musician)|Eden]] \"Drugs\" (2016)\n* [[Wolf Alice]] \"[[You're a Germ|You're A Germ]]\" (2015)<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm3436820/|title=Craig Bernard|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n* [[Kaskade]] \"Never Sleep Alone\" (2015)<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://imvdb.com/n/craig-bernard|title=Craig Bernard|website=IMVDb|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n* [[Grouplove]] \"I'm With You\" (2014)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Chromeo]] \"Come Alive\" (2014)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Avicii]] \"[[Hey Brother]]\" (2013)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Grouplove]] \"Ways to Go\" (2013)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Colbie Caillat]] \"Hold On\" (2013)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Grouplove]] \"Shark Attack\" (2013)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Bruno Mars]] \"[[Locked Out of Heaven]]\" (2012)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Kerli]] \"[[The Lucky Ones (song)|The Lucky Ones]]\" (2012)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Bruno Mars]] \"[[When I Was Your Man]]\" (2012)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Twin Atlantic]] \"What is Light? Where is Laughter?\" (2011)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[CeeLo Green|Ceelo Green]] \"[[I Want You (Cee-Lo Green song)|I want You]]\" (2011)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Inna]] \"[[Club Rocker]]\" (2011)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Awolnation]] \"[[Kill Your Heroes]]\" (2011)<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[imdbname:3436820|Craig Bernard on IMDb]]\n* [https://imvdb.com/n/craig-bernard Craig Bernard on IMVMDb]\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.mvdbase.com/person.php?id=C3569|title=Craig Bernard|website=Music Video DataBase|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912055824/http://www.mvdbase.com/person.php?id=C3569|archivedate=12 September 2017|url-status=live}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bernard, Craig}}\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian film producers]]\n[[Category:American music video directors]]\n[[Category:American music video producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian music video directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Music video producers]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ambrosiawater", "label": "safe", "comment": "director, not capitalised", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Craig_Bernard"}
{"title_page": "Petraio", "text_new": "The '''Petraio''' is a widely-known geographical and urban area in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once the expansive upper agricultural area (later becoming the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]), connecting with lower neighborhoods along the way, terminating in the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood of downtown Naples. \n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the interconnected pathways were originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were gradually trafficked and inhabited, they were improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone paths, walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\nProminent sub-sections include Gradini (steps) del Petraio, Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio, Vico (alley) del Petraio, Largo (widening) del Petraio, Rampe (ramp) del Petraio, Salita (climb) del Petraio, Via Filippo Palizzi and Via Achille Vianelli. Near one of its many prominent architectural features, Villa Santarella, the Petraio is colloquially called ''La Santarella''. \n\nMostly framed with residential buildings, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture, from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi'' (small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself) &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served on Via Filippo Palizzi by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]] at Salita del Petraio and Via Filippo Palizzi.  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>  \n\nThe Petraio are a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Petraio''' is a widely-known geographical and urban area in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once the expansive upper agricultural area (later becoming the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]), connecting with lower neighborhoods along the way, terminating in the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood of downtown Naples. \n\nMostly framed with residential buildings, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture, from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi'' (small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself) &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref>, the interconnected pathways were originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were gradually trafficked and inhabited, they were improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone paths, walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\nIts prominent sections include Gradini (steps) del Petraio, Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio, Vico (alley) del Petraio, Largo (widening) del Petraio, Rampe (ramp) del Petraio, Salita (climb) del Petraio, Via Filippo Palizzi and Via Achille Vianelli. Near one of its many prominent architectural features, Villa Santarella, the Petraio is colloquially called ''La Santarella''. \n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served on Via Filippo Palizzi by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]] at Salita del Petraio and Via Filippo Palizzi.  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>  \n\nThe Petraio are a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petraio"}
{"title_page": "Michael Harris (public policy scholar)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name = '''Michael Harris'''\n| image = Michael Harris PhD Academic.png\n| image_size = 250px\n| birth_name = Michael Harris\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1956|01|06|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1956|01|06}} -->\n| nationality = [[United States]] and [[Israel]]\n| alma_mater = [[Bar-Ilan University]]<br />[[Tel Aviv University]]<br />[[Indiana University Bloomington]]\n| occupation = Dean and Professor at [[Tennessee State University]]\n| spouse = Tali Harris\n| children = Ronen, Asaf, Amit\n| website = {{url|http://www.tnstate.edu/cpsua/people/harris.aspx|Website}}\n}}\n\n'''Michael Harris''' (born January 6, 1956) is an Israeli-American  public policy scholar and university administrator. He is currently [[Dean (education)|Dean]] and professor at the College of Public Service at [[Tennessee State University]].<ref name=\"Tennessee State University Dean, Department Heads, and Staff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tnstate.edu/cpsua/people/deandepartmentheads.aspx|title=Tennessee State University Dean, Department Heads, and Staff|publisher=tnstate.edu|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nBorn in [[South Africa]], Michael Harris immigrated with his family to Israel as a child.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/kids/kokomoans/a-childhood-story-from-a-notable-kokomoan-indiana-university-kokomo/article_4d39ef04-978e-11e0-839f-001cc4c03286.html|title=A CHILDHOOD STORY FROM A NOTABLE KOKOMOAN: Indiana University Kokomo Chancellor Michael Harris|last=|first=|date=15 June 2011|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He is married to Tali Harris and has three sons, Ronen, Asaf, and Amit.\n\nHarris holds a bachelor's degree in economics and business administration from [[Bar-Ilan University]] (1982), a master's degree in public policy from [[Tel-Aviv University]] (1986), and a Ph.D. in public policy from [[Indiana University Bloomington|Indiana University]] (1993). After initially specializing in electoral politics and public policy, Harris' current research focuses on academic decision-making and developing learner-centered curricula within universities to improve student performance outcomes.\n\nHarris served in the Israel Defense Forces and retired at the rank of major with active combat experience.<ref name=\"Chancellor Michael Harris: Indiana University Ceremonies\">{{cite web|url=http://ceremonies.iu.edu/iuk/biography.shtml|title=Dr. Harris' archived faculty page from Indiana University|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130708145217/http://ceremonies.iu.edu/iuk/biography.shtml|archivedate=2013-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Leadership and academic career==\n\nHarris is dean of and professor at the College of Public Service at [[Tennessee State University]],<ref name=\"Tennessee State University Dean, Department Heads, and Staff\" /> guiding the College to its first ever appearance on [[U.S. News & World Report|US News]] 2019 rankings as one of the best public affairs programs in the nation<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tnstatenewsroom.com/archives/24014|title=TSU COLLEGE OF PUBLIC SERVICE LISTED AS ONE OF BEST IN THE NATION|last=McLendon|first=Michael|date=26 April 2019|website=TSU Newsroom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. The College's Graduate [[Public Affairs]] program was ranked for a second consecutive time in 2020, securing the important distinction as the second highest [[ranked]] program at an [[HBCU]] with a [[Network of Schools of Public Policy, Affairs, and Administration|NASPAA]] accredited graduate public affairs program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-public-affairs-schools/public-affairs-rankings|title=Best Public Affairs Programs|last=|first=|date=|website=U.S. News & World Report|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to 2012, Harris served as the sixth chancellor of [[Indiana University Kokomo]] and a professor of public and environmental affairs, business, and education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/news/flint/2010/03/kettering_provost_to_fill_um-f.html|title=Kettering Provost to fill UM-Flint chancellor's old job as IU-Kokomo chancellor|last=Mostafavi|first=Beata|date=24 March 2010|website=Michigan Live|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/news/michael-harris-selected-as-new-chancellor-of-iu-kokomo/article_fb37578e-3684-11df-b5ef-001cc4c002e0.html|title=Michael Harris selected as new chancellor of IU Kokomo|last=|first=|date=23 March 2010|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"Chancellor Michael Harris: Indiana University Ceremonies\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://webapp1.dlib.indiana.edu/iubot/view?docId=2011-04-15&doc.view=print&toc.depth=1&toc.id=0&brand=iubot|title=Indiana University Board of Trustees Business meeting minutes Bloomington|date=April 2012|publisher=webapp1.dlib.indiana.edu|accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.iu.edu/news/page/normal/13828.html|title=Michael Harris selected as new chancellor of IU Kokomo: IU News Room: Indiana University|publisher=Newsinfo.iu.edu|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> Harris led IU Kokomo through the process of adding 10 new degree programs to the Kokomo campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/news/local_news/iu-kokomo-introduces-new-degree-programs/article_3565d9f4-9c09-11e0-b494-001cc4c03286.html|title=IU Kokomo introduces new degree programs|last=|first=|date=27 June 2011|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Harris instituted online classes and increased the number of Friday classes offered. He also developed an athletic program, overseeing the development of four sports (men's basketball, men's cross country, women's cross country, and women's volleyball), which resulted in the university joining the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA) in 2012<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/sports/iuk/naia-approves-indiana-university-kokomo-for-membership/article_b7f4e4e4-87e7-11e1-9684-001a4bcf887a.html|title=NAIA approves Indiana University Kokomo for membership|last=|first=|date=16 April 2012|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iukcougars.com/article/5#.Xl0mLJNKiUk|title=INDIANA UNIVERSITY KOKOMO ADDS CROSS-COUNTRY TO SPORTS PROGRAM|last=|first=|date=20 March 2012|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. During his time as Chancellor at IUK, Harris was appointed by Governor [[Mitch Daniels]] to serve on the Indiana Automotive Council<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/news/local_news/governor-appoints-chancellor-harris-to-indiana-automotive-council/article_6af3d818-d562-11e0-8eb3-001cc4c03286.html|title=Governor appoints Chancellor Harris to Indiana Automotive Council|last=|first=|date=2 September 2011|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. In January 2012, under the leadership of Michael Harris, IU Kokomo received a $1.25 million gift from Milt and Jean Cole to fund a new wellness and fitness center.<ref>{{cite web | title=Milt and Jean Cole family of Logansport donates $1.25 million to Indiana University Kokomo | publisher=Kokomo Perspective | accessdate=2015-09-12 | url=http://kokomoperspective.com/news/local_news/milt-and-jean-cole-family-of-logansport-donates-million-to/article_9e2a0d82-3b8e-11e1-9b75-0019bb2963f4.html}}</ref> At the time, this was the largest cash gift ever received on IU's Kokomo campus.<ref>{{cite web | title=Milt and Jean Cole family of Logansport donates $1.25 million to Indiana University Kokomo | url=http://philanthropynewsdigest.org/news/indiana-university-kokomo-receives-1.25-million-gift | accessdate=2015-09-12 | publisher=Philanthropy News Digest}}</ref> The new facility, The Milt and Jean Cole Family Wellness and Fitness Center, opened in August, 2013. Under his leadership, [[U.S. News & World Report]] ranked Indiana University Kokomo among the best regional campuses in the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]], a first-ever mention for the campus that includes a Tier 1 level, and the only [[Indiana University|IU]] regional campus to receive this recognition<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/xtra/education/u-s-news-world-report-ranks-iu-kokomo-among-the/article_222a4536-fdde-11e1-a3e3-001a4bcf887a.html|title=U.S. News & World Report ranks IU Kokomo among the best Regional Campuses|last=|first=|date=13 September 2012|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. While serving as Chancellor, Harris was presented the Phoenix II (a sculpture and plaque) from the faculty, staff, and students of the university's fine arts program<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMTSNv_q9eA&t=20s|title=IU Kokomo Chancellor Recognized|last=|first=|date=25 March 2015|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. Reflecting on his time as Chancellor at IUK, [[Kokomo Perspective]] [[Publisher]], Don Wilson, said of Harris, \"The university is much better off for his time here. Student housing, new degree programs, record enrollment, a new fitness center, the athletic program -- they all originated on his watch\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/kp/publisher-looks-back-at-people-who-made-the-news-in/article_ac76b76e-4360-11e4-a8e7-13eba65de0a9.html|title=Publisher looks back at people who made the news in the Perspective|last=Wilson|first=Don|date=28 September 2014|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nHe also served as provost and vice president of academic affairs and student affairs at [[Kettering University]] (formerly [[General Motors Institute of Technology|GMI]]) in [[Flint, Michigan]], from 2007 to 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.kettering.edu/news/new-provost-dr-michael-harris|title=NEW PROVOST DR. MICHAEL HARRIS|last=|first=|date=13 July 2007|website=Kettering University News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2010/03/kettering_provost_to_fill_um-f.html|title=Kettering Provost to fill UM-Flint chancellor's old job as IU-Kokomo chancellor System|publisher=mlive.com|date=March 2010|accessdate=2010-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100611005074/en/Kettering-University-Commencement-June-12-358-Graduates|title=Dr. Michael Harris - Commencement Speaker|work=Business Wire|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> During his time at Kettering, Harris built multiple partnerships and secured unprecedented grants and gifts, such as $1.6 million from the Wisconsin-based Kern Foundation for the study of entrepreneurship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.kettering.edu/news/16-million-gift|title=$1.6 MILLION GIFT|last=Mroczek|first=Patricia|date=24 May 2010|website=Kettering University News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. While serving as Provost and Vice President of Academic Affairs at Kettering University, Harris was a leader in a collaborative effort among Swedish Biogas International, the City of [[Flint, Michigan|Flint]], Kettering University, and the [[Michigan Economic Development Corporation]] that resulted in $951,500 grant from the [[United States Department of Energy|U.S. Department of Energy]] (DOE) to advance the production of [[biogas]] and [[biomethane]] at the Flint Center of Energy Excellence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.michiganbusiness.org/press-releases/2010/02/granholm-hails-u.s.-department-of-energy-award-to-flint-center-of-energy-excellence/|title=Granholm Hails U.S. Department of Energy Award to Flint Center of Energy Excellence|last=Brown|first=Megan|date=18 February 2010|website=Michigan Economic Development Corporation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Harris also built partnerships with other Michigan colleges and universities to ensure that Kettering University students had the best opportunities. One such partnership was an agreement signed by Kettering University and [[Michigan State University College of Human Medicine]], which provided an enhanced opportunity for Kettering [[Pre-medical|pre-med]] students to attend [[medical school]]. Additionally, Harris was a vital member of the delegation that built unprecedented partnerships between Kettering and Chinese universities, government institutions, and businesses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.catarc.ac.cn/ac_en/content/20090430/9988.html|title=Kettering University Delegation Visited CATARC|last=|first=|date=28 April 2009|website=CATARC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.kettering.edu/news/seeking-presence-china|title=SEEKING A PRESENCE IN CHINA|last=Mroczek|first=Pat|date=27 June 2008|website=Kettering University News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In one of his final acts before leaving the university to become chancellor of [[Indiana University Kokomo]], Harris led a four-hour [[negotiation]] session that resulted in [[Kettering University|Kettering]] becoming one of the first few universities in the world to form an agreement with the Chinese Automotive Technology and Research Center (CATARC), one of the most prestigious automotive research centers in [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/news/flint/2010/05/kettering_university_strengthe.html|title=Kettering University strengthens ties to China, forming new partnerships that could make it the \"Chinese General Motors Institute\"|last=Mostafavi|first=Beata|date=17 March 2010|website=Michigan Live|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHarris was the vice president for academic affairs at [[Ferris State University]] (2004\u20132007), he was successful in strengthening the areas of academics, teaching, research, scholarship, retention, assessment, and service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20070514006178/en/Kettering-University-Names-Dr.-Michael-Harris-Provost#.UuNVUP30Ab0|title=Kettering University Names Michael Harris as New Provost and Vice President - Business Wire|publisher=Businesswire.com|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> Prior to joining Ferris State, he was a faculty member in the Department of Political Science and subsequently associate provost at [[Eastern Michigan University]] (1994\u20132004).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://caine.emich.edu/archives/findingaids/html/Michael_Harris_papers.html|title=Professor Michael Harris Papers|publisher=Eastern Michigan University Archives}}</ref> During this time at Eastern Michigan, Harris was instrumental in vital efforts, such as overseeing the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools|North Central Association]], [[Higher Learning Commission]] Self-Study Steering Committee in his capacity as Interim [[Provost (education)|Provost]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commons.emich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1950&context=focus|title=NCA Self-Study Report was a Collaborative Effort|last=Podell|first=Ron|date=27 February 2001|website=Eastern Michigan Focus News for Faculty & Staff|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> that resulted in the University's re-accreditation by NCA, HLC. While at Eastern Michigan University, he received the Michigan Association of Governing Boards Distinguished Faculty Award,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.iu.edu/news/page/normal/13828.html|title=Michael Harris selected as new chancellor of IU Kokomo|last=|first=|date=23 March 2010|website=IU Newsroom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/news/michael-harris-selected-as-new-chancellor-of-iu-kokomo/article_fb37578e-3684-11df-b5ef-001cc4c002e0.html|title=Michael Harris selected as new chancellor of IU Kokomo|last=|first=|date=23 March 2010|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which was an annual award to distinguished faculty and outstanding students \u201cin recognition of a treasured Michigan resource and the promise it represents for our states\u2019 future.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gvsu.lyrasistechnology.org/repositories/2/resources/11|title=Michigan Association of Governing Boards award files|last=|first=|date=|website=Grand Valley State University Special Collections and University Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Harris also served as a faculty member in the Graduate Program of Public Policy at [[Tel Aviv University]] (1993-1994).<ref name=\"Chancellor Michael Harris: Indiana University Ceremonies\" />\n\nIn 2012, the Hebrew-language newspaper, [[Maariv (newspaper)|Maariv]], named Harris as the most successful Israeli academic working outside of Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishpostopinion.com/Jewishpost/JPO-IN_7-4-12.pdf|title=IU Kokomo chancellor recognized as top Israeli academic in the world working outside Israel|last=|first=|date=4 July 2012|website=The Jewish Post & Opinion (Indiana Edition)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slideshare.net/michaelharrischancellor/maariv-full-article-29437195|title=IU Kokomo Chancellor Recognized, Top Academic, Maariv, Michael Harris\u2026|author=Michael Harris Chancellor IU Kokomo (6th)|publisher=Slideshare.net|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.iu.edu/news/page/normal/22530.html&t=IUKokomochancellorrecognizedastopIsraeliacademicintheworldworkingoutsideIsrael|title=IU Kokomo chancellor recognized as top Israeli academic in the world working outside Israel: IU News Room: Indiana University|publisher=Newsinfo.iu.edu|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> The [[Kokomo Perspective]] also named him their Person of the Year for 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.kokomoperspective.com/news/local_news/kokomo-perspective-s-person-of-the-year-michael-harris/article_8c2ec302-2a77-11e1-b3b7-001871e3ce6c.html?mode=jqm|title=Kokomo Perspective's Person of the Year Michael Harris|work=Kokomo Perspective|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/kp/publisher-looks-back-at-people-who-made-the-news-in/article_ac76b76e-4360-11e4-a8e7-13eba65de0a9.html|title=Publisher looks back at people who made the news in the Perspective|publisher=Kokomo Perspective|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> As Chancellor, Harris was named Honorary Wing Commander of the 434th Air Refueling Wing by [[Grissom Air Reserve Base]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grissom.afrc.af.mil/News/Article/174869/dr-harris-six-others-selected-for-honorary-commanders-program/|title=Dr. Harris, six others selected for honorary commanders program|last=|first=|date=8 January 2012|website=Grissom Air Reserve Base|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.is/9IGmC|title=Grissom Air Force Base names IU Kokomo Chancellor Harris 'Honorary Wing Commander 2012'|last=|first=|date=January 2012|website=Indiana University Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grissom.afrc.af.mil/Home/Photos/igphoto/2000156546/|title=Dr. Harris, honorary wing commander|website=www.grissom.afrc.af.mil|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grissom.afrc.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/174832/grissoms-honorary-commanders-part-1/|title=Grissom's Honorary Commanders-Part 1|accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref> which took place on February 12, 2012<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0ROu3kr6UYU|title=Michael Harris IU Kokomo, Michael Harris Honorary Commander|last=|first=|date=3 April 2015|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and also included the honorary commanders participating  in the [[Grissom Air Reserve Base]]'s celebration of being designated a \"Tree City USA\" by the [[National Arbor Day Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grissom.afrc.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/174774/keeping-grissom-green/|title=Keeping Grissom green|last=|first=|date=30 April 2012|website=Grissom Air Reserve Base|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He also received the Best in Class 2009 Award from the Keen Entrepreneurship Education Network<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kettering.edu/news/best-class|title='Best in Class'|work=Kettering University|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> and an honorary doctorate in educational administration from [[Ave Maria College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.president.iu.edu/speeches/archive/2010/20101022-01.shtml|title=\"Imagine What the Future Holds: The Installation of Michael Harris as Chancellor of IU Kokomo\"|last=|first=|date=22 October 2010|website=Indiana University President's Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Harris worked with the [[Tennessee Bureau of Investigation]] (TBI) to develop a unique certificate program, known as the Public Administration Executive Leadership Certificate or \"Command College\". In addition, he was named as a consultant to the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tnstatenewsroom.com/archives/18221|title=TSU DEAN NAMED CONSULTANT TO THE TENNESSEE BUREAU OF INVESTIGATION|last=Buggs|first=C.|date=18 November 2015|website=Tennessee State University Newsroom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tbinews.wordpress.com/2015/11/02/new-education-option-enhancing-career-development-for-tbi-personnel/|title=New Education Option Enhancing Career Development for TBI Personnel|work=Tennessee Bureau of Investigation|accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n\n*''The Learner-Centered Curriculum: Design and Implementation'' (with R. Cullen and R. Hill). San Francisco: Jossey-Bass, 2012. {{ISBN|978-1118049556}}\n*''Leading the Learner-Centered Campus: An Administrator's Framework for Improving Student Learning Outcomes'' (with R. Cullen). San Francisco: Jossey-Bass, 2010. {{ISBN|978-0470402986}}\n*''Innovation and Entrepreneurship in State and Local Government'' (ed. with R. Kinney). Lexington Books, 2003. {{ISBN|978-0739109267}}\n*''Term Limits'' (with G. Doron). Lexington Books, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0739102138}}\n*''Public Policy and Electoral Reform: The Case of Israel'' (with G. Doron). Lexington Books, 2000. {{ISBN|978-0739101346}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harris, Michael}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:South African Jews]]\n[[Category:People from Kokomo, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Indiana University faculty]]\n[[Category:Kettering University faculty]]\n[[Category:Ferris State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Tel Aviv University faculty]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:Bar-Ilan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Tel Aviv University alumni]]\n[[Category:Indiana University Bloomington alumni]]\n[[Category:South African emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:Israeli emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Israel]]\n[[Category:Eastern Michigan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tennessee State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Public administration scholars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name = '''Michael Harris'''\n| image = Michael Harris PhD Academic.png\n| image_size = 250px\n| birth_name = Michael Harris\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1956|01|06|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1956|01|06}} -->\n| nationality = [[United States]] and [[Israel]]\n| alma_mater = [[Bar-Ilan University]]<br />[[Tel Aviv University]]<br />[[Indiana University Bloomington]]\n| occupation = Dean and Professor at [[Tennessee State University]]\n| spouse = Tali Harris\n| children = Ronen, Asaf, Amit\n| website = {{url|http://www.tnstate.edu/cpsua/people/harris.aspx|Website}}\n}}\n\n'''Michael Harris''' (born January 6, 1956) is an Israeli-American  public policy scholar and university administrator. He is currently [[Dean]] and professor at the College of Public Service at [[Tennessee State University]].<ref name=\"Tennessee State University Dean, Department Heads, and Staff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tnstate.edu/cpsua/people/deandepartmentheads.aspx|title=Tennessee State University Dean, Department Heads, and Staff|publisher=tnstate.edu|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nBorn in [[South Africa]], Michael Harris immigrated with his family to Israel as a child.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/kids/kokomoans/a-childhood-story-from-a-notable-kokomoan-indiana-university-kokomo/article_4d39ef04-978e-11e0-839f-001cc4c03286.html|title=A CHILDHOOD STORY FROM A NOTABLE KOKOMOAN: Indiana University Kokomo Chancellor Michael Harris|last=|first=|date=15 June 2011|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He is married to Tali Harris and has three sons, Ronen, Asaf, and Amit.\n\nHarris holds a bachelor's degree in economics and business administration from [[Bar-Ilan University]] (1982), a master's degree in public policy from [[Tel-Aviv University]] (1986), and a Ph.D. in public policy from [[Indiana University Bloomington|Indiana University]] (1993). After initially specializing in electoral politics and public policy, Harris' current research focuses on academic decision-making and developing learner-centered curricula within universities to improve student performance outcomes.\n\nHarris served in the Israel Defense Forces and retired at the rank of major with active combat experience.<ref name=\"Chancellor Michael Harris: Indiana University Ceremonies\">{{cite web|url=http://ceremonies.iu.edu/iuk/biography.shtml|title=Dr. Harris' archived faculty page from Indiana University|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130708145217/http://ceremonies.iu.edu/iuk/biography.shtml|archivedate=2013-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Leadership and academic career==\n\nHarris is dean of and professor at the College of Public Service at [[Tennessee State University]],<ref name=\"Tennessee State University Dean, Department Heads, and Staff\" /> guiding the College to its first ever appearance on [[U.S. News & World Report|US News]] 2019 rankings as one of the best public affairs programs in the nation<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tnstatenewsroom.com/archives/24014|title=TSU COLLEGE OF PUBLIC SERVICE LISTED AS ONE OF BEST IN THE NATION|last=McLendon|first=Michael|date=26 April 2019|website=TSU Newsroom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. The College's Graduate [[Public Affairs]] program was ranked for a second consecutive time in 2020, securing the important distinction as the second highest [[ranked]] program at an [[HBCU]] with a [[Network of Schools of Public Policy, Affairs, and Administration|NASPAA]] accredited graduate public affairs program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-public-affairs-schools/public-affairs-rankings|title=Best Public Affairs Programs|last=|first=|date=|website=U.S. News & World Report|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to 2012, Harris served as the sixth chancellor of [[Indiana University Kokomo]] and a professor of public and environmental affairs, business, and education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/news/flint/2010/03/kettering_provost_to_fill_um-f.html|title=Kettering Provost to fill UM-Flint chancellor's old job as IU-Kokomo chancellor|last=Mostafavi|first=Beata|date=24 March 2010|website=Michigan Live|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/news/michael-harris-selected-as-new-chancellor-of-iu-kokomo/article_fb37578e-3684-11df-b5ef-001cc4c002e0.html|title=Michael Harris selected as new chancellor of IU Kokomo|last=|first=|date=23 March 2010|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"Chancellor Michael Harris: Indiana University Ceremonies\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://webapp1.dlib.indiana.edu/iubot/view?docId=2011-04-15&doc.view=print&toc.depth=1&toc.id=0&brand=iubot|title=Indiana University Board of Trustees Business meeting minutes Bloomington|date=April 2012|publisher=webapp1.dlib.indiana.edu|accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.iu.edu/news/page/normal/13828.html|title=Michael Harris selected as new chancellor of IU Kokomo: IU News Room: Indiana University|publisher=Newsinfo.iu.edu|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> Harris led IU Kokomo through the process of adding 10 new degree programs to the Kokomo campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/news/local_news/iu-kokomo-introduces-new-degree-programs/article_3565d9f4-9c09-11e0-b494-001cc4c03286.html|title=IU Kokomo introduces new degree programs|last=|first=|date=27 June 2011|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Harris instituted online classes and increased the number of Friday classes offered. He also developed an athletic program, overseeing the development of four sports (men's basketball, men's cross country, women's cross country, and women's volleyball), which resulted in the university joining the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA) in 2012<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/sports/iuk/naia-approves-indiana-university-kokomo-for-membership/article_b7f4e4e4-87e7-11e1-9684-001a4bcf887a.html|title=NAIA approves Indiana University Kokomo for membership|last=|first=|date=16 April 2012|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iukcougars.com/article/5#.Xl0mLJNKiUk|title=INDIANA UNIVERSITY KOKOMO ADDS CROSS-COUNTRY TO SPORTS PROGRAM|last=|first=|date=20 March 2012|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. During his time as Chancellor at IUK, Harris was appointed by Governor [[Mitch Daniels]] to serve on the Indiana Automotive Council<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/news/local_news/governor-appoints-chancellor-harris-to-indiana-automotive-council/article_6af3d818-d562-11e0-8eb3-001cc4c03286.html|title=Governor appoints Chancellor Harris to Indiana Automotive Council|last=|first=|date=2 September 2011|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. In January 2012, under the leadership of Michael Harris, IU Kokomo received a $1.25 million gift from Milt and Jean Cole to fund a new wellness and fitness center.<ref>{{cite web | title=Milt and Jean Cole family of Logansport donates $1.25 million to Indiana University Kokomo | publisher=Kokomo Perspective | accessdate=2015-09-12 | url=http://kokomoperspective.com/news/local_news/milt-and-jean-cole-family-of-logansport-donates-million-to/article_9e2a0d82-3b8e-11e1-9b75-0019bb2963f4.html}}</ref> At the time, this was the largest cash gift ever received on IU's Kokomo campus.<ref>{{cite web | title=Milt and Jean Cole family of Logansport donates $1.25 million to Indiana University Kokomo | url=http://philanthropynewsdigest.org/news/indiana-university-kokomo-receives-1.25-million-gift | accessdate=2015-09-12 | publisher=Philanthropy News Digest}}</ref> The new facility, The Milt and Jean Cole Family Wellness and Fitness Center, opened in August, 2013. Under his leadership, [[U.S. News & World Report]] ranked Indiana University Kokomo among the best regional campuses in the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]], a first-ever mention for the campus that includes a Tier 1 level, and the only [[Indiana University|IU]] regional campus to receive this recognition<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/xtra/education/u-s-news-world-report-ranks-iu-kokomo-among-the/article_222a4536-fdde-11e1-a3e3-001a4bcf887a.html|title=U.S. News & World Report ranks IU Kokomo among the best Regional Campuses|last=|first=|date=13 September 2012|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. While serving as Chancellor, Harris was presented the Phoenix II (a sculpture and plaque) from the faculty, staff, and students of the university's fine arts program<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMTSNv_q9eA&t=20s|title=IU Kokomo Chancellor Recognized|last=|first=|date=25 March 2015|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. Reflecting on his time as Chancellor at IUK, [[Kokomo Perspective]] [[Publisher]], Don Wilson, said of Harris, \"The university is much better off for his time here. Student housing, new degree programs, record enrollment, a new fitness center, the athletic program -- they all originated on his watch\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/kp/publisher-looks-back-at-people-who-made-the-news-in/article_ac76b76e-4360-11e4-a8e7-13eba65de0a9.html|title=Publisher looks back at people who made the news in the Perspective|last=Wilson|first=Don|date=28 September 2014|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nHe also served as provost and vice president of academic affairs and student affairs at [[Kettering University]] (formerly [[General Motors Institute of Technology|GMI]]) in [[Flint, Michigan]], from 2007 to 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.kettering.edu/news/new-provost-dr-michael-harris|title=NEW PROVOST DR. MICHAEL HARRIS|last=|first=|date=13 July 2007|website=Kettering University News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2010/03/kettering_provost_to_fill_um-f.html|title=Kettering Provost to fill UM-Flint chancellor's old job as IU-Kokomo chancellor System|publisher=mlive.com|date=March 2010|accessdate=2010-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100611005074/en/Kettering-University-Commencement-June-12-358-Graduates|title=Dr. Michael Harris - Commencement Speaker|work=Business Wire|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> During his time at Kettering, Harris built multiple partnerships and secured unprecedented grants and gifts, such as $1.6 million from the Wisconsin-based Kern Foundation for the study of entrepreneurship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.kettering.edu/news/16-million-gift|title=$1.6 MILLION GIFT|last=Mroczek|first=Patricia|date=24 May 2010|website=Kettering University News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. While serving as Provost and Vice President of Academic Affairs at Kettering University, Harris was a leader in a collaborative effort among Swedish Biogas International, the City of [[Flint, Michigan|Flint]], Kettering University, and the [[Michigan Economic Development Corporation]] that resulted in $951,500 grant from the [[United States Department of Energy|U.S. Department of Energy]] (DOE) to advance the production of [[biogas]] and [[biomethane]] at the Flint Center of Energy Excellence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.michiganbusiness.org/press-releases/2010/02/granholm-hails-u.s.-department-of-energy-award-to-flint-center-of-energy-excellence/|title=Granholm Hails U.S. Department of Energy Award to Flint Center of Energy Excellence|last=Brown|first=Megan|date=18 February 2010|website=Michigan Economic Development Corporation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Harris also built partnerships with other Michigan colleges and universities to ensure that Kettering University students had the best opportunities. One such partnership was an agreement signed by Kettering University and [[Michigan State University College of Human Medicine]], which provided an enhanced opportunity for Kettering [[Pre-medical|pre-med]] students to attend [[medical school]]. Additionally, Harris was a vital member of the delegation that built unprecedented partnerships between Kettering and Chinese universities, government institutions, and businesses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.catarc.ac.cn/ac_en/content/20090430/9988.html|title=Kettering University Delegation Visited CATARC|last=|first=|date=28 April 2009|website=CATARC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.kettering.edu/news/seeking-presence-china|title=SEEKING A PRESENCE IN CHINA|last=Mroczek|first=Pat|date=27 June 2008|website=Kettering University News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In one of his final acts before leaving the university to become chancellor of [[Indiana University Kokomo]], Harris led a four-hour [[negotiation]] session that resulted in [[Kettering University|Kettering]] becoming one of the first few universities in the world to form an agreement with the Chinese Automotive Technology and Research Center (CATARC), one of the most prestigious automotive research centers in [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/news/flint/2010/05/kettering_university_strengthe.html|title=Kettering University strengthens ties to China, forming new partnerships that could make it the \"Chinese General Motors Institute\"|last=Mostafavi|first=Beata|date=17 March 2010|website=Michigan Live|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHarris was the vice president for academic affairs at [[Ferris State University]] (2004\u20132007), he was successful in strengthening the areas of academics, teaching, research, scholarship, retention, assessment, and service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20070514006178/en/Kettering-University-Names-Dr.-Michael-Harris-Provost#.UuNVUP30Ab0|title=Kettering University Names Michael Harris as New Provost and Vice President - Business Wire|publisher=Businesswire.com|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> Prior to joining Ferris State, he was a faculty member in the Department of Political Science and subsequently associate provost at [[Eastern Michigan University]] (1994\u20132004).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://caine.emich.edu/archives/findingaids/html/Michael_Harris_papers.html|title=Professor Michael Harris Papers|publisher=Eastern Michigan University Archives}}</ref> During this time at Eastern Michigan, Harris was instrumental in vital efforts, such as overseeing the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools|North Central Association]], [[Higher Learning Commission]] Self-Study Steering Committee in his capacity as Interim [[Provost (education)|Provost]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commons.emich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1950&context=focus|title=NCA Self-Study Report was a Collaborative Effort|last=Podell|first=Ron|date=27 February 2001|website=Eastern Michigan Focus News for Faculty & Staff|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> that resulted in the University's re-accreditation by NCA, HLC. While at Eastern Michigan University, he received the Michigan Association of Governing Boards Distinguished Faculty Award,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.iu.edu/news/page/normal/13828.html|title=Michael Harris selected as new chancellor of IU Kokomo|last=|first=|date=23 March 2010|website=IU Newsroom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/news/michael-harris-selected-as-new-chancellor-of-iu-kokomo/article_fb37578e-3684-11df-b5ef-001cc4c002e0.html|title=Michael Harris selected as new chancellor of IU Kokomo|last=|first=|date=23 March 2010|website=Kokomo Perspective|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which was an annual award to distinguished faculty and outstanding students \u201cin recognition of a treasured Michigan resource and the promise it represents for our states\u2019 future.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gvsu.lyrasistechnology.org/repositories/2/resources/11|title=Michigan Association of Governing Boards award files|last=|first=|date=|website=Grand Valley State University Special Collections and University Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Harris also served as a faculty member in the Graduate Program of Public Policy at [[Tel Aviv University]] (1993-1994).<ref name=\"Chancellor Michael Harris: Indiana University Ceremonies\" />\n\nIn 2012, the Hebrew-language newspaper, [[Maariv (newspaper)|Maariv]], named Harris as the most successful Israeli academic working outside of Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishpostopinion.com/Jewishpost/JPO-IN_7-4-12.pdf|title=IU Kokomo chancellor recognized as top Israeli academic in the world working outside Israel|last=|first=|date=4 July 2012|website=The Jewish Post & Opinion (Indiana Edition)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slideshare.net/michaelharrischancellor/maariv-full-article-29437195|title=IU Kokomo Chancellor Recognized, Top Academic, Maariv, Michael Harris\u2026|author=Michael Harris Chancellor IU Kokomo (6th)|publisher=Slideshare.net|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.iu.edu/news/page/normal/22530.html&t=IUKokomochancellorrecognizedastopIsraeliacademicintheworldworkingoutsideIsrael|title=IU Kokomo chancellor recognized as top Israeli academic in the world working outside Israel: IU News Room: Indiana University|publisher=Newsinfo.iu.edu|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> The [[Kokomo Perspective]] also named him their Person of the Year for 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.kokomoperspective.com/news/local_news/kokomo-perspective-s-person-of-the-year-michael-harris/article_8c2ec302-2a77-11e1-b3b7-001871e3ce6c.html?mode=jqm|title=Kokomo Perspective's Person of the Year Michael Harris|work=Kokomo Perspective|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kokomoperspective.com/kp/publisher-looks-back-at-people-who-made-the-news-in/article_ac76b76e-4360-11e4-a8e7-13eba65de0a9.html|title=Publisher looks back at people who made the news in the Perspective|publisher=Kokomo Perspective|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> As Chancellor, Harris was named Honorary Wing Commander of the 434th Air Refueling Wing by [[Grissom Air Reserve Base]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grissom.afrc.af.mil/News/Article/174869/dr-harris-six-others-selected-for-honorary-commanders-program/|title=Dr. Harris, six others selected for honorary commanders program|last=|first=|date=8 January 2012|website=Grissom Air Reserve Base|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.is/9IGmC|title=Grissom Air Force Base names IU Kokomo Chancellor Harris 'Honorary Wing Commander 2012'|last=|first=|date=January 2012|website=Indiana University Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grissom.afrc.af.mil/Home/Photos/igphoto/2000156546/|title=Dr. Harris, honorary wing commander|website=www.grissom.afrc.af.mil|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grissom.afrc.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/174832/grissoms-honorary-commanders-part-1/|title=Grissom's Honorary Commanders-Part 1|accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref> which took place on February 12, 2012<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0ROu3kr6UYU|title=Michael Harris IU Kokomo, Michael Harris Honorary Commander|last=|first=|date=3 April 2015|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and also included the honorary commanders participating  in the [[Grissom Air Reserve Base]]'s celebration of being designated a \"Tree City USA\" by the [[National Arbor Day Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grissom.afrc.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/174774/keeping-grissom-green/|title=Keeping Grissom green|last=|first=|date=30 April 2012|website=Grissom Air Reserve Base|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He also received the Best in Class 2009 Award from the Keen Entrepreneurship Education Network<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kettering.edu/news/best-class|title='Best in Class'|work=Kettering University|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> and an honorary doctorate in educational administration from [[Ave Maria College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.president.iu.edu/speeches/archive/2010/20101022-01.shtml|title=\"Imagine What the Future Holds: The Installation of Michael Harris as Chancellor of IU Kokomo\"|last=|first=|date=22 October 2010|website=Indiana University President's Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Harris worked with the [[Tennessee Bureau of Investigation]] (TBI) to develop a unique certificate program, known as the Public Administration Executive Leadership Certificate or \"Command College\". In addition, he was named as a consultant to the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tnstatenewsroom.com/archives/18221|title=TSU DEAN NAMED CONSULTANT TO THE TENNESSEE BUREAU OF INVESTIGATION|last=Buggs|first=C.|date=18 November 2015|website=Tennessee State University Newsroom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tbinews.wordpress.com/2015/11/02/new-education-option-enhancing-career-development-for-tbi-personnel/|title=New Education Option Enhancing Career Development for TBI Personnel|work=Tennessee Bureau of Investigation|accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n\n*''The Learner-Centered Curriculum: Design and Implementation'' (with R. Cullen and R. Hill). San Francisco: Jossey-Bass, 2012. {{ISBN|978-1118049556}}\n*''Leading the Learner-Centered Campus: An Administrator's Framework for Improving Student Learning Outcomes'' (with R. Cullen). San Francisco: Jossey-Bass, 2010. {{ISBN|978-0470402986}}\n*''Innovation and Entrepreneurship in State and Local Government'' (ed. with R. Kinney). Lexington Books, 2003. {{ISBN|978-0739109267}}\n*''Term Limits'' (with G. Doron). Lexington Books, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0739102138}}\n*''Public Policy and Electoral Reform: The Case of Israel'' (with G. Doron). Lexington Books, 2000. {{ISBN|978-0739101346}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harris, Michael}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:South African Jews]]\n[[Category:People from Kokomo, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Indiana University faculty]]\n[[Category:Kettering University faculty]]\n[[Category:Ferris State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Tel Aviv University faculty]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:Bar-Ilan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Tel Aviv University alumni]]\n[[Category:Indiana University Bloomington alumni]]\n[[Category:South African emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:Israeli emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Israel]]\n[[Category:Eastern Michigan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tennessee State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Public administration scholars]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "