{"title_page": "John Pudney", "text_new": "{{redirect|Pudney|the New Zealand cricketer|Richard Pudney}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n'''John Sleigh Pudney''' (19 January 1909 \u2013 10 November 1977) was a British poet, journalist and writer.  He was known especially for his popular poetry written during the [[Second World War|Second World War]], but he also wrote novels, short stories and children's fiction (including the Hartwarp books). Pudney also wrote broad-ranging non-fiction, often commissioned, which served as his primary source of income. \n\n==Education and Early Career==\nJohn Pudney was born at [[Langley, Berkshire|Langley Marish]], the only son of Henry William Pudney (a farmer and countryman) and Mabel Sleigh Pudney. He was educated at [[Gresham's School]], [[Holt, Norfolk|Holt]], where he first encountered [[W. H. Auden]], [[Benjamin Britten]], and [[Humphrey Spender]]. He left school in 1925 at the age of sixteen, and spent several years working as an estate agent and studying to become a surveyor. However, he began contributing articles to the [[News Chronicle|News Chronicle]] at the same time, also writing short stories and channelling his love of the countryside into verse.<ref name=dnb>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/31573Roger Lubbock, \u2018Pudney, John Sleigh (1909\u20131977)\u2019, rev. Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, May 2006]</ref> At this time he was one of a group of young writers (including [[Dylan Thomas]], [[George Barker (poet)|George Barker]] and [[David Gascoyne]]) who gathered about the well-known bookshop at No 4, Parton Street, near London's [[Red Lion Square]], run by David Archer.<ref>[https://www.penpushermagazine.co.uk/magazine/issues/article/215/ Goodall, Anna. 'Parton Street Bookshop' in ''Pen Pusher'']</ref> His first published collection of verse, ''Spring Encounter'', came out in 1933 from [[Methuen Publishing|Methuen]] and gained the attention of [[Lady Ottoline Morrell]] who became a patron. Pudney also wrote for [[The Listener]], and worked as a producer at the [[BBC]], where he produced the radio play ''Hadrian's Wall'' with text by Auden and music by Britten, which was broadcast from Newcastle on 25 November 1937.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IMFZ8a8aNHUC&pg=PT116&lpg=PT116&dq=John+Pudney+Benjamin+Britten&source=bl&ots=MUhRGApbmp&sig=ACfU3U2b1caNszL8RMuBi3jjBlRlW4z0Lw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi8-c67k8zoAhUJesAKHRsaDzIQ6AEwCXoECAsQOA#v=onepage&q=John%20Pudney%20Benjamin%20Britten&f=false Warden, C. ''British Avant-Garde Theatre'' (2012)]</ref><ref>[https://www.nmcrec.co.uk/roman-wall-blues NMC Music. ''Benjamin Britten, Roman Wall Blues'']</ref> While at the BBC he also wrote one of the first plays for television - ''Edna's Fruit Hat'' - which was broadcast on 27 January 1939.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/c9ebf9521e9540b4bd20fbc5126034c5 ''Radio Times'' Issue 799, 22 January 1939, p 17]</ref> His first novel, ''Jacobson's Ladder'', describing literary and criminal life in 1930s [[Soho]], appeared in 1938.<ref>[https://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/taro/uthrc/00112/00112-P.html John Pudney Papers at the Harry Ransom Research Center]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-GiDDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=John+Pudney+Jacobsons%27+Ladder&source=bl&ots=7jsAyWhnUt&sig=ACfU3U0ODy1oYxRY7bMp-r4kBZAi75sLFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjlxsiGn8zoAhWxolwKHdxmCjYQ6AEwDnoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=John%20Pudney&f=false Cottrell, Anna. ''London Writing of the 1930s'' (2018) p 88]</ref>\n\n==War Poetry==\nIt was the advent of the Second World War that enabled Pudney to find his subject - the effect that war has on the lives of ordinary people - and with it, his audience.<ref name=times>''The Times'' obituary, 11 November 1977, p 17</ref> In 1940 he was commissioned into the [[Royal Air Force]] as an intelligence officer and as a member of the [[Air Ministry]]'s Creative Writers Unit - a non-combatant role. It was while he was serving as squadron intelligence officer at [[RAF St Eval]] in Cornwall that Pudney wrote one of the best-known poems of the war.<ref name=dnb/> ''For Johnny'' evoked popular fellow-feeling in the London of 1941.<ref>[http://www.carolinemdavies.co.uk/2012/06/07/collected-poems-john-pudney/ Davies, Caroline. ''Collected Poems, John Pudney'']</ref> Written during an air raid, it was published first in the ''News Chronicle'', and featured significantly in the film ''[[The Way to the Stars]]'':\n\n<poem>\nDo not despair\nFor Johnny-head-in-air;\nHe sleeps as sound\nAs Johnny underground.\n\nFetch out no shroud\nFor Johnny-in-the-cloud;\nAnd keep your tears\nFor him in after years.\n\nBetter by far\nFor Johnny-the-bright-star,\nTo keep your head,\nAnd see his children fed.\n</poem>\n\nPudney published several collections of poetry during the war which between them sold over a quarter of a million copies.<ref name=white>White, Michael. 'Johnny Head-in-Air', in ''The Guardian'', 6 April, 1972, p 10</ref>\n\n==Later Career==\nIn the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|UK General Election of July 1945]], Pudney stood as the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] candidate for [[Sevenoaks (UK Parliament constituency)|Sevenoaks]], polling 14,947 votes, or 36 per cent.<ref>''The International Who's Who'' (Europa Publications Limited, 1963) p. 857</ref><ref>[http://www.psr.keele.ac.uk/area/uk/ge45/i17.htm UK General Election results July 1945] at keele.ac.uk, accessed 10 January 2009</ref>\n\nAfter the war he continued to write and worked as a journalist and editor. He was the book critic for [[The Daily Express]] from 1945 and with the ''[[News Review]]'' from 1948 to 1950. He then shifted into publishing, as a director and literary adviser to Evans Brothers, Ltd (1950-1953) and Putnam & Co Ltd (1953-1963). In 1953 he wrote the documentary [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0238961/   ''Elizabeth is Queen''] for [[Associated British Picture Corporation|Associated British Path\u00e9]], which received a [[BAFTA]] award. Of his novels, ''The Net'' (1952, set in an aeronautical research station) and ''Thin Air'' (1961) were well received.<ref name=times/> [[The Net (1953 film)|''The Net'']] was filmed by director [[Anthony Asquith]] in 1953.<ref>Pendo, Stephen. ''Aviation in the Cinema''. Lanham, Maryland: Scarecrow Press, 1985. {{ISBN|0-8-1081-746-2}}.</ref> His children's books, including the 'Fred and I' series (''Monday Adventure'' etc), and the Hartwarp adventures for younger children, were popular and sold well in the 1950s and 1960s, but haven't remained in print. Between 1949 and 1963 he edited an annual anthology called ''Pick of Today's Short Stories''. However, poetry remained the most important to him. His later work, from the collection ''Spill Out'' (1967) onward took on a more ironic stance, but still vernacular rather than academic, a period reflected in his second Selected Poems collection of 1973. One of his book blurbs describes him as \"a poet who just missed being an intellectual\".<ref name=white/>\n\n==Private Life==\nOn 30 October 1934 Pudney married Crystal Selwyn Herbert, the daughter of [[A. P. Herbert]], the writer and [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] [[Member of Parliament]]. They had two daughters and a son, but were divorced. In 1955 he married his second wife, Monica Forbes Curtis of the [[Forbes family]]. She helped him recover from his alcoholism, to which he publicly confessed in 1965 and emerged cured in 1967 - despite a hit-and-run accident in the middle that broke both his legs and dislocated his shoulder.<ref name=white/> That process became a subject for his writing. ''Spill Out'' was written \"half of it on the booze and half off, and he didn't remember which half was which\".<ref name=white/> In 1976 he developed cancer of the throat from which he died a year later in much pain. He wrote about his illness unflinchingly in his autobiographical ''Thank Goodness for Cake'', posthumously published in 1978.<ref name=dnb/> His grandson [[Toby Perkins]] is the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Chesterfield]].\n\n==Works==\n\n===Poetry===\n*''Spring Encounter'' (1933)\n*''Open the Sky'' ([[Boriswood]] 1934)\n*''Dispersal Point and other Air Poems'' (1942)\n*''The Grass Grew All Round'' (1942)\n*''Beyond This Disregard'' (1943) poems\n*''South of Forty'' (1943) poems\n*''Ten Summers'': Poems 1933-1943 (1944)\n*''Almanack of Hope'': Sonnets (1944)\n*''Air Force Poetry'' (1944) (anthology, edited with Henry Treese)\n*''Flight above Cloud'' (1944)\n*''World Still There'' (1945)\n*Selected Poems (1946)\n*''Low Life'' (1947)\n*''Commemorations'' (1948)\n*''Sixpenny Songs'' (1953)\n*Collected Poems (1957)\n*''Spill Out'': Poems and Ballads (1967)\n*''Spandrels'': Poems and Ballads (1969)\n*''Take This Orange'': Poems and Ballads (1971)\n*Selected Poems 1967-1973 (1973)\n*''Living in a One-Sided House'' (1976) poems\n*''Writers' Workshop'', poetry anthology publication, editor with [[Norman Hidden]] and [[Michael Johnson (editor)|Michael Johnson]] (from 1967)<ref>Durham University. [http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ark/32150_s17w62f823m.xml Norman Hidden Collection]</ref>\n\n===Novels===\n*''Jacobson's Ladder'' (1938)\n*''Shuffley Wanderers'' (1948)\n*''The Accomplice'' (1950)\n*''Hero of a Summer's Day'' (1951)\n*''The Net'' (1952)\n*''A Ring for Luck'' (1953)\n*''Trespass in the Sun'' (1957)\n*''Thin Air'' (1961)\n*''Tunnel to the Sky'' (1965)\n*''The Long Time Growing Up'' (1971) novel\n\n===Short stories===\n*''And Lastly the Fireworks'' ([[Boriswood]] 1935)\n*''Uncle Arthur and other stories'' (1939)\n*''Edna's Fruit Hat'' (1946)\n*''It Breathed Down My Neck'' (1946)\n*''The Europeans'': Fourteen tales of a Continent (1948)\n*''The Pick of Today's Short Stories'', 14 volumes (1949-1963), anthologies, editor\n*''The Trampoline'' (1959)\n\n===For Children===\n*''Saturday Adventure'' (1950) \"a story for boys\"\n*''Sunday Adventure'' (1951)\n*''Monday Adventure: The Secrets of Blackmead Abbey'' (1952)\n*''Tuesday Adventure'' (1953)\n*''Wednesday Adventure'' (1954)\n*''Thursday Adventure'' (1955)\n*''Friday Adventure'' (1956)\n*''Spring Adventure'' (1961)\n*''Summer Adventure'' (1962)\n*''The Hartwarp Light Railway'' (1962)\n*''The Hartwarp Balloon'' (1963)\n*''The Hartwarp Circus'' (1963)\n*''The Hartwarp Bakehouse'' (1964)\n*''Autumn Adventure'' (1964)\n*''The Hartwarp E''xplosion'' (1965)\n*''Winter Adventure (1965)\n*''The Grandfather Clock'' (1966)\n*''The Hartwarp Jets'' (1967)\n\n===Biography===\n*''Who Only England Know'' (1943)\n*''Home & Away - An Autobiographical Gambit'' (1960)\n*''Thank Goodness for Cake'' (1978)\n\n===Non Fiction===\n* ''Who Only England Know'' (1943)\n* ''The Air Battle of Malta'' (1944) (HMSO Information Books)\n* ''Atlantic Bridge'' (1945) HMSO (Information Books)\n*''Estuary, a Romance'' (1947)\n* ''Music on the South Bank: An Appreciation of The Royal Festival Hall''.(1951)\n*''His Majesty King George VI'' (1952)\n*''The Thomas Cook Story'' (1953)\n*''The Queen's People'' (1953), photographs by [[Izis Bidermanas]]\n*''The Smallest Room'': a Discreet Survey Through the Ages (1954)\n*''The Book of Leisure'' (1957) editor\n*''The Leisure-Hour Companion'' (1959)\n*''The Seven Skies'' (1959), history of BOAC\n*''A Pride of Unicorns'': [[Richard Atcherley|Richard]] and [[David Atcherley]] of the R.A.F. (1960)\n*''Bristol Fashion''. Some Account of the Earlier Days of Bristol Aviation (1960)\n*''The Camel Fighter'' (1964)\n*''The Golden Age of Stea''m (1967)\n*''Flight and Flying'' (1968) editor\n*''Suez: De Lesseps' Canal'' (1968)\n*''A Draught of Contentment''. The Story of the Courage Group.(1971)\n*''Crossing London's River'': the Bridges, Ferries and Tunnels Crossing the Thames Tideway in London (1972) \n*''Brunel and His World'' (1974)\n*''London's Docks'' (1975)\n*''Lewis Carroll and His World'' (1976)\n*''John Wesley and His World'' (1978)\n\n==References==\n*[https://norman.hrc.utexas.edu/fasearch/findingAid.cfm?eadid=00112s Biographical Sketch of John Pudney at the University of Texas]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/person.asp?LinkID=mp18871 John Pudney at the National Portrait Gallery]\n*[http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/pudney_john John Pudney entry in SFE The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction]\n* [https://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/taro/uthrc/00112/00112-P.html John Pudney: An Inventory of His Papers at the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pudney, John}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gresham's School]]\n[[Category:People from Slough]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:20th-century British poets]]\n[[Category:British male poets]]\n[[Category:English children's writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Pudney|the New Zealand cricketer|Richard Pudney}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n'''John Sleigh Pudney''' (19 January 1909 \u2013 10 November 1977) was a British poet, journalist and writer.  He was known especially for his popular poetry written during the [[Second World War|Second World War]], but he also wrote novels, short stories and children's fiction (including the Hartwarp books). Pudney also wrote broad-ranging non-fiction, often commissioned, which served as his primary source of income. \n\n==Education and Early Career==\nJohn Pudney was born at [[Langley, Berkshire|Langley Marish]], the only son of Henry William Pudney (a farmer and countryman) and Mabel Sleigh Pudney. He was educated at [[Gresham's School]], [[Holt, Norfolk|Holt]], where he first encountered [[W. H. Auden]], [[Benjamin Britten]], and [[Humphrey Spender]]. He left school in 1925 at the age of sixteen, and spent several years working as an estate agent and studying to become a surveyor. However, he began contributing articles to the [[News Chronicle|News Chronicle]] at the same time, also writing short stories and channelling his love of the countryside into verse.<ref name=dnb>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/31573Roger Lubbock, \u2018Pudney, John Sleigh (1909\u20131977)\u2019, rev. Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, May 2006]</ref> At this time he was one of a group of young writers (including [[Dylan Thomas]], [[George Barker (poet)|George Barker]] and [[David Gascoyne]]) who gathered about the well-known bookshop at No 4, Parton Street, near London's [[Red Lion Square]], run by David Archer.<ref>[https://www.penpushermagazine.co.uk/magazine/issues/article/215/ Goodall, Anna. 'Parton Street Bookshop' in ''Pen Pusher'']</ref> His first published collection of verse, ''Spring Encounter'', came out in 1933 from [[Methuen Publishing|Methuen]] and gained the attention of [[Lady Ottoline Morrell]] who became a patron. Pudney also wrote for [[The Listener]], and worked as a producer at the [[BBC]], where he produced the radio play ''Hadrian's Wall'' with text by Auden and music by Britten, which was broadcast from Newcastle on 25 November 1937.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IMFZ8a8aNHUC&pg=PT116&lpg=PT116&dq=John+Pudney+Benjamin+Britten&source=bl&ots=MUhRGApbmp&sig=ACfU3U2b1caNszL8RMuBi3jjBlRlW4z0Lw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi8-c67k8zoAhUJesAKHRsaDzIQ6AEwCXoECAsQOA#v=onepage&q=John%20Pudney%20Benjamin%20Britten&f=false Warden, C. ''British Avant-Garde Theatre'' (2012)]</ref><ref>[https://www.nmcrec.co.uk/roman-wall-blues NMC Music. ''Benjamin Britten, Roman Wall Blues'']</ref> While at the BBC he also wrote one of the first plays for television - ''Edna's Fruit Hat'' - which was broadcast on 27 January 1939.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/c9ebf9521e9540b4bd20fbc5126034c5 ''Radio Times'' Issue 799, 22 January 1939, p 17]</ref> His first novel, ''Jacobson's Ladder'', describing literary and criminal life in 1930s [[Soho]], appeared in 1938.<ref>[https://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/taro/uthrc/00112/00112-P.html John Pudney Papers at the Harry Ransom Research Center]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-GiDDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=John+Pudney+Jacobsons%27+Ladder&source=bl&ots=7jsAyWhnUt&sig=ACfU3U0ODy1oYxRY7bMp-r4kBZAi75sLFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjlxsiGn8zoAhWxolwKHdxmCjYQ6AEwDnoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=John%20Pudney&f=false Cottrell, Anna. ''London Writing of the 1930s'' (2018) p 88]</ref>\n\n==War Poetry==\nIt was the advent of the Second World War that enabled Pudney to find his subject - the effect that war has on the lives of ordinary people - and with it, his audience.<ref name=times>''The Times'' obituary, 11 November 1977, p 17</ref> In 1940 he was commissioned into the [[Royal Air Force]] as an intelligence officer and as a member of the [[Air Ministry]]'s Creative Writers Unit - a non-combatant role. It was while he was serving as squadron intelligence officer at [[RAF St Eval]] in Cornwall that Pudney wrote one of the best-known poems of the war.<ref name=dnb/> ''For Johnny'' evoked popular fellow-feeling in the London of 1941.<ref>[http://www.carolinemdavies.co.uk/2012/06/07/collected-poems-john-pudney/ Davies, Caroline. ''Collected Poems, John Pudney'']</ref> Written during an air raid, it was published first in the ''News Chronicle'', and featured significantly in the film ''[[The Way to the Stars]]'':\n\n<poem>\nDo not despair\nFor Johnny-head-in-air;\nHe sleeps as sound\nAs Johnny underground.\n\nFetch out no shroud\nFor Johnny-in-the-cloud;\nAnd keep your tears\nFor him in after years.\n\nBetter by far\nFor Johnny-the-bright-star,\nTo keep your head,\nAnd see his children fed.\n</poem>\n\nPudney published several collections of poetry during the war which between them sold over a quarter of a million copies.<ref name=white>White, Michael. 'Johnny Head-in-Air', in ''The Guardian'', 6 April, 1972, p 10</ref>\n\n==Later Career==\nIn the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|UK General Election of July 1945]], Pudney stood as the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] candidate for [[Sevenoaks (UK Parliament constituency)|Sevenoaks]], polling 14,947 votes, or 36 per cent.<ref>''The International Who's Who'' (Europa Publications Limited, 1963) p. 857</ref><ref>[http://www.psr.keele.ac.uk/area/uk/ge45/i17.htm UK General Election results July 1945] at keele.ac.uk, accessed 10 January 2009</ref>\n\nAfter the war he continued to write and worked as a journalist and editor. He was the book critic for [[The Daily Express]] from 1945 and with the ''[[News Review]]'' from 1948 to 1950. He then shifted into publishing, as a director and literary adviser to Evans Brothers, Ltd (1950-1953) and Putnam & Co Ltd (1953-1963). In 1953 he wrote the documentary [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0238961/   ''Elizabeth is Queen''] for [[Associated British Picture Corporation|Associated British Path\u00e9]], which received a [[BAFTA]] award. Of his novels, ''The Net'' (1952, set in an aeronautical research station) and ''Thin Air'' (1961) were well received.<ref name=times/> [[The Net (1953 film)|''The Net'']] was filmed by director [[Anthony Asquith]] in 1953.<ref>Pendo, Stephen. ''Aviation in the Cinema''. Lanham, Maryland: Scarecrow Press, 1985. {{ISBN|0-8-1081-746-2}}.</ref> His children's books, including the 'Fred and I' series (''Monday Adventure'' etc), and the Hartwarp adventures for younger children, were popular and sold well in the 1950s and 1960s, but haven't remained in print. Between 1949 and 1963 he edited an annual anthology called ''Pick of Today's Short Stories''. However, poetry remained the most important to him. His later work, from the collection ''Spill Out'' (1967) onward took on a more ironic stance, but still vernacular rather than academic, a period reflected in his second Selected Poems collection of 1973. One of his book blurbs describes him as \"a poet who just missed being an intellectual\".<ref name=white/>\n\n==Private Life==\nOn 30 October 1934 Pudney married Crystal Selwyn Herbert, the daughter of [[A. P. Herbert]], the writer and [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] [[Member of Parliament]]. They had two daughters and a son, but were divorced. In 1955 he married his second wife, Monica Forbes Curtis of the [[Forbes family]]. She helped him recover from his alcoholism, to which he publicly confessed in 1965 and emerged cured in 1967. That process became a subject for his writing. In 1976 he developed cancer of the throat from which he died a year later in much pain. He wrote about his illness unflinchingly in his autobiographical ''Thank Goodness for Cake'', posthumously published in 1978.<ref name=dnb/> His grandson [[Toby Perkins]] is the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Chesterfield]].\n\n==Works==\n\n===Poetry===\n*''Spring Encounter'' (1933)\n*''Open the Sky'' ([[Boriswood]] 1934)\n*''Dispersal Point and other Air Poems'' (1942)\n*''The Grass Grew All Round'' (1942)\n*''Beyond This Disregard'' (1943) poems\n*''South of Forty'' (1943) poems\n*''Ten Summers'': Poems 1933-1943 (1944)\n*''Almanack of Hope'': Sonnets (1944)\n*''Air Force Poetry'' (1944) (anthology, edited with Henry Treese)\n*''Flight above Cloud'' (1944)\n*''World Still There'' (1945)\n*Selected Poems (1946)\n*''Low Life'' (1947)\n*''Commemorations'' (1948)\n*''Sixpenny Songs'' (1953)\n*Collected Poems (1957)\n*''Spill Out'': Poems and Ballads (1967)\n*''Spandrels'': Poems and Ballads (1969)\n*''Take This Orange'': Poems and Ballads (1971)\n*Selected Poems 1967-1973 (1973)\n*''Living in a One-Sided House'' (1976) poems\n*''Writers' Workshop'', poetry anthology publication, editor with [[Norman Hidden]] and [[Michael Johnson (editor)|Michael Johnson]] (from 1967)<ref>Durham University. [http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ark/32150_s17w62f823m.xml Norman Hidden Collection]</ref>\n\n===Novels===\n*''Jacobson's Ladder'' (1938)\n*''Shuffley Wanderers'' (1948)\n*''The Accomplice'' (1950)\n*''Hero of a Summer's Day'' (1951)\n*''The Net'' (1952)\n*''A Ring for Luck'' (1953)\n*''Trespass in the Sun'' (1957)\n*''Thin Air'' (1961)\n*''Tunnel to the Sky'' (1965)\n*''The Long Time Growing Up'' (1971) novel\n\n===Short stories===\n*''And Lastly the Fireworks'' ([[Boriswood]] 1935)\n*''Uncle Arthur and other stories'' (1939)\n*''Edna's Fruit Hat'' (1946)\n*''It Breathed Down My Neck'' (1946)\n*''The Europeans'': Fourteen tales of a Continent (1948)\n*''The Pick of Today's Short Stories'', 14 volumes (1949-1963), anthologies, editor\n*''The Trampoline'' (1959)\n\n===For Children===\n*''Saturday Adventure'' (1950) \"a story for boys\"\n*''Sunday Adventure'' (1951)\n*''Monday Adventure: The Secrets of Blackmead Abbey'' (1952)\n*''Tuesday Adventure'' (1953)\n*''Wednesday Adventure'' (1954)\n*''Thursday Adventure'' (1955)\n*''Friday Adventure'' (1956)\n*''Spring Adventure'' (1961)\n*''Summer Adventure'' (1962)\n*''The Hartwarp Light Railway'' (1962)\n*''The Hartwarp Balloon'' (1963)\n*''The Hartwarp Circus'' (1963)\n*''The Hartwarp Bakehouse'' (1964)\n*''Autumn Adventure'' (1964)\n*''The Hartwarp E''xplosion'' (1965)\n*''Winter Adventure (1965)\n*''The Grandfather Clock'' (1966)\n*''The Hartwarp Jets'' (1967)\n\n===Biography===\n*''Who Only England Know'' (1943)\n*''Home & Away - An Autobiographical Gambit'' (1960)\n*''Thank Goodness for Cake'' (1978)\n\n===Non Fiction===\n* ''Who Only England Know'' (1943)\n* ''The Air Battle of Malta'' (1944) (HMSO Information Books)\n* ''Atlantic Bridge'' (1945) HMSO (Information Books)\n*''Estuary, a Romance'' (1947)\n* ''Music on the South Bank: An Appreciation of The Royal Festival Hall''.(1951)\n*''His Majesty King George VI'' (1952)\n*''The Thomas Cook Story'' (1953)\n*''The Queen's People'' (1953), photographs by [[Izis Bidermanas]]\n*''The Smallest Room'': a Discreet Survey Through the Ages (1954)\n*''The Book of Leisure'' (1957) editor\n*''The Leisure-Hour Companion'' (1959)\n*''The Seven Skies'' (1959), history of BOAC\n*''A Pride of Unicorns'': [[Richard Atcherley|Richard]] and [[David Atcherley]] of the R.A.F. (1960)\n*''Bristol Fashion''. Some Account of the Earlier Days of Bristol Aviation (1960)\n*''The Camel Fighter'' (1964)\n*''The Golden Age of Stea''m (1967)\n*''Flight and Flying'' (1968) editor\n*''Suez: De Lesseps' Canal'' (1968)\n*''A Draught of Contentment''. The Story of the Courage Group.(1971)\n*''Crossing London's River'': the Bridges, Ferries and Tunnels Crossing the Thames Tideway in London (1972) \n*''Brunel and His World'' (1974)\n*''London's Docks'' (1975)\n*''Lewis Carroll and His World'' (1976)\n*''John Wesley and His World'' (1978)\n\n==References==\n*[https://norman.hrc.utexas.edu/fasearch/findingAid.cfm?eadid=00112s Biographical Sketch of John Pudney at the University of Texas]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/person.asp?LinkID=mp18871 John Pudney at the National Portrait Gallery]\n*[http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/pudney_john John Pudney entry in SFE The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction]\n* [https://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/taro/uthrc/00112/00112-P.html John Pudney: An Inventory of His Papers at the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pudney, John}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gresham's School]]\n[[Category:People from Slough]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:20th-century British poets]]\n[[Category:British male poets]]\n[[Category:English children's writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Sfjohna", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrivate Life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Pudney"}
{"title_page": "Siamosaurus", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], ([[Barremian]]) {{Fossilrange|130|125}}\n| image = Siamosaurus_tooth_by_PaleoGeek.png\n| image_caption = Illustrated [[holotype]] tooth, with [[Penny (British decimal coin)|British penny]] for scale\n| taxon = Siamosaurus\n| authority = Buffetaut & Ingavat, 1986\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = *'''''S. suteethorni''''' <small>Buffetaut & Ingavat, 1986 ([[type species|type]])</small>\n| synonyms = *'''''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'''''? <small>Hou, Yeh & Zhao, 1975</small>\n}}\n'''''Siamosaurus''''' (meaning \"Siamese lizard\") is a potentially [[Dubious name|dubious]] [[genus]] of [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived 130 to 125 million years ago, during the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Period (geologic time)|Period]] of what is now [[Isan|northeastern]] [[Thailand]]. It is the first spinosaurid reported from Asia and is known only from tooth [[Fossil|fossils]]; the first of which were found in the [[Sao Khua Formation]], with more teeth later recovered from the younger [[Khok Kruat Formation]]. The [[type species]] '''''Siamosaurus suteethorni''''', whose name honours the Thai [[palaeontologist]] [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], was formally described in [[1986 in paleontology|1986]]. One tooth possibly belonging to the genus was discovered in the Japanese [[Sebayashi Formation]] in 1994, and a tooth similar to it was found at the same site in 2015. In 2009, four teeth from China's [[Xinlong Formation]] were assigned to the spinosaurid species '''''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis''''', which may be the same animal as ''Siamosaurus''. Most of the aforementioned teeth were originally attributed to [[Marine reptile|marine reptiles]]. A partial spinosaurid skeleton from the Khok Kruat Formation was described in 2007, but whether it belongs to ''Siamosaurus'' or not is unclear.\n\nThe [[holotype]] tooth is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} long and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm|}} wide at the base. Since it is a tooth taxon, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s body size and weight are uncertain, though it has been estimated at between {{Convert|5.1 to 9.1|m||abbr=}} and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}. ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s teeth were straight, oval to circular in cross section, and lined with distinct lengthwise ridges. The tooth's [[Tooth enamel|enamel]] was wrinkled, similar to that of teeth from the related genus ''[[Baryonyx]]''. ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s identity has been questioned by many palaeontologists, who argue that its teeth are too similar to those of contemporaneous aquatic reptiles for it to be confidently classed as a dinosaur. Other researchers, who agree that the teeth are spinosaur in origin, deem them too similar to those of other Early Cretaceous spinosaurs to unequivocally raise a new genus. Based on characteristics of its teeth, ''Siamosaurus'' has been placed within the [[Spinosaurinae]] [[subfamily]].\n\nLike all spinosaurids, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth were conical, with reduced or absent [[Serration|serrations]]. This made them suitable for impaling rather than tearing flesh, a trait typically seen in largely [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) animals. Its relatives are known to have also consumed [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]] and small to medium-sized dinosaurs, and there is fossil evidence of ''Siamosaurus'' eating [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] dinosaurs, either via scavenging or hunting. ''Siamosaurus'' lived in a [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] habitat of [[Floodplain|floodplains]] and meandering rivers, where it coexisted with other theropod, sauropod, and (in at least the Khok Kruat Formation) [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontian]] dinosaurs. [[Isotope analysis]] indicates spinosaurids may have had [[semiaquatic]] habits, and ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s role as a piscivorous predator might have reduced the prominence of contemporaneous aquatic reptiles.\n\n== History of discovery ==\n[[File:Cretaceous_strata_in_northeast_and_southeastern_Thailand.png|thumb|left|Geological map of the [[Khorat Plateau]] in northeast Thailand]]\n\nThe [[Sao Khua Formation]], where the first ''Siamosaurus'' [[Fossil|fossils]] were discovered, is part of the [[Khorat Group]].<ref name=\":0\">Buffetaut, E.; and Ingevat, R. (1986). Unusual theropod dinosaur teeth from the Upper Jurassic of Phu Wiang, northeastern Thailand. Rev. Paleobiol. 5: 217-220.</ref> The formation is dated to the [[Barremian]] [[Stage (geology)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Geological period|Period]], 130 to 125 million years ago,<ref name=\":15\" /> though it was formerly believed to be [[Late Jurassic]] in age.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Racey|first=Andrew|last2=G. S. Goodall|first2=J|date=2009-05-12|title=Palynology and stratigraphy of the Mesozoic Khorat Group red bed sequences from Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/249552008|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|volume=315|issue=1|pages=69\u201383|citeseerx=10.1.1.1030.8425|doi=10.1144/SP315.6|bibcode=2009GSLSP.315...69R}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|last=Bertin|first=Tor|date=2010-12-08|title=A catalogue of material and review of the Spinosauridae|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/235679976|journal=PalArch's Journal of Vertebrate Palaeontology|volume=7}}</ref> Out of all [[Mesozoic]] formations in northeastern Thailand, the Sao Khua is the most abundant and diversified in [[vertebrate]] fossil discoveries.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> The Khorat Group exhibits taxa only of continental origin, with no definitive evidence for marine fossils or [[Sedimentary rock|sedimentary]] structures found so far. In 1963, Yoshitsugu Kobayashi of the [[Hokkaido University]] reported ichthyosaur and [[Plesiosauria|plesiosaur]] teeth from the Sao Khua Formation, but these have now been identified as belonging to ''Siamosaurus'' and a [[Crocodilia|crocodilian]] respectively.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/books/book/1678/late-palaeozoic-and-mesozoic-continental|title=Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Continental Ecosystems in SE Asia {{!}} GeoScienceWorld Books {{!}} GeoScienceWorld|website=pubs.geoscienceworld.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, French [[Paleontologists|palaeontologist]] [[Eric Buffetaut|\u00c9ric Buffetaut]] and his Thai colleague Rucha Ingavat described a set of fossil teeth recovered from the Phu Pratu Teema locality of the Sao Khua Formation, in [[Khon Kaen Province]]. They reached no conclusion as to what animal they originated from, their opinion being that the specimens belonged \"either to an unusual [[Theropoda|theropod]] [[dinosaur]], or to some unknown crocodilian\". In [[1986 in paleontology|1986]], a reassessment of the remains by the same authors attributed them to a new [[genus]] and [[species]] of [[spinosaurid]] theropod, which they named ''Siamosaurus suteethorni''. The generic name alludes to the ancient name of Thailand, \"Siam\", while the specific name honours Thai [[geologist]] and palaeontologist [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], and his contributions to vertebrate palaeontology discoveries in Thailand.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:Museum_Dinosaur_KK.jpg|thumb|The [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]] houses [[fossil]] replicas and a sculpture of ''Siamosaurus''<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Boonchai|first=N|last2=Grote|first2=Paul|last3=Jintasakul|first3=P|date=2009-01-01|title=Paleontological parks and museums and prominent fossil sites in Thailand and their importance in the conservation of fossils|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/286206751|journal=PaleoParks - the Protection and Conservation of Fossil Sites Worldwide|pages=75\u201395}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1264683/centre-of-the-northeast|title=Centre of the Northeast|last=Karnjanatawe|first=Karnjana|date=June 2017|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23}}</ref>]]\n\nThe best-preserved specimen from the series, designated DMR TF 2043a, was chosen as the [[holotype]] of ''Siamosaurus.<ref name=\":0\" />'' The [[Paratype|paratypes]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Siamosaurussuteethorni|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=Mickey|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> comprise eight other well-preserved teeth catalogued as DMR TF 2043b to i. The original fossils are currently housed in the palaeontological collection of the [[Department of Mineral Resources (Thailand)|Department of Mineral Resources]], [[Bangkok]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Other fossils later referred to the genus, including two well preserved teeth (SM2016-1-147 and SM2016-1-165) and one [[Cervical vertebrae|cervical]] (neck) [[vertebra]] (SM2016-1-067) are stored in the [[Sirindhorn Museum]], [[Kalasin Province]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219641|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219713|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219621|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> Isolated ''Siamosaurus'' teeth are common in the Sao Khua Formation.<ref name=\":1\" /> Large hypothetical sculptures of the animal have been erected in various places across northeast Thailand, including Si Wiang Dinosaur Park,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1137381/jurassic-park-vs-the-weekend-warrior|title=Jurassic Park vs the weekend warrior|last=Mekloy|first=Pongpet|date=November 2016|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23}}</ref> the [[Siam Paragon]] shopping mall in Bangkok,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/formerly-one-of-the-biggest-smiles-in-the-land-of-smiles|title=Formerly one of the biggest smiles in the Land of Smiles|last=hermes|first=|date=2017-05-04|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-08-23|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/life/Dinosaurs-in-the-big-city-30273487.html|title=Dinosaurs in the big city - The Nation|work=The Nation|access-date=2018-08-23|language=en}}</ref> and the [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]].<ref name=\":10\" /> The animal was also illustrated on Thai postage stamps released in 1997, along with fellow Thai dinosaurs ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]] sirindhornae,'' ''[[Siamotyrannus]] isanensis'', and ''[[Psittacosaurus]] sattayaraki''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/scott2002standar00scot_1|title=Scott 2002 standard postage stamp catalogue. Volume 6 : countries of the world, So-Z|last=Scott Publishing Co|date=2001|publisher=Sidney, OH : Scott Pub. Co.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Khok_Kruat_spinosaurid_neural_spine.png|thumb|left|upright=0.60|Illustrated [[neural spine]] of a [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] from the [[Khok Kruat Formation]]]]\n\n''Siamosaurus'' is the first reported spinosaurid dinosaur from Asia,<ref name=\":14\" /> and subsequently to its naming, material resembling or possibly belonging to the taxon has been found across the continent. In 1975, Chinese palaeontologist Hou Lian-Hai and colleagues described five teeth as a new species of the [[Pliosauroidea|pliosauroid]] ''[[Sinopliosaurus]]'', which they named ''S. fusuiensis''.<ref>Hou, L., Yeh, H. and Zhao, X. (1975). Fossil reptiles from Fusui, Kwangshi. ''Vertebrata PalAsiatica'' 13; 24-33</ref> Four of these teeth (one was not found in the museum collection) were reassigned by Buffetaut and colleagues in 2008 to a ''Siamosaurus''-like taxon and referred to as [[\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis|\"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'']]''.'' The researchers deemed \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' as \"closely related to, if not identical with\" ''Siamosaurus suteethorni.<ref name=\"EBetal082\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360}}</ref>'' American palaeontologist Mickey Mortimer informally placed \"''S.''\" ''fusuiensis'' under the latter genus as a tentative additional species, ''Siamosaurus fusuiensis'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Sinopliosaurusfusuiensis|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=M.|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref> an analysis also held by Spanish palaeontologists Rub\u00e9n Molina-P\u00e9rez and Asier Larramendi in 2016.''<ref name=\":20\" />'' In 2019, it was referred by Thai palaeontologist Wongko Kamonlak and colleagues as the \"Chinese ''Siamosaurus''\".''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wongko|first=Kamonlak|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Khamha|first3=Suchada|last4=Lauprasert|first4=Komsorn|date=2019-03-31|title=Spinosaurid theropod teeth from the Red Beds of the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://li01.tci-thaijo.org/index.php/tnh/article/view/181194|journal=Tropical Natural History|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=8\u201320|issn=2586-9892}}</ref>'' The original specimens were collected from China's Early Cretaceous [[Xinlong Formation]], in which indeterminate spinosaurs are frequently reported, though most of them are hard to differentiate from those of Japan or Thailand without further fossil material besides teeth''.''<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite journal|last=MO|first=JINYOU|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|last4=Amiot|first4=Romain|last5=Cavin|first5=Lionel|last6=Cuny|first6=Gilles|last7=Suteethorn|first7=Varavudh|last8=SUTEETHORN|first8=SURAVECH|last9=JIANG|first9=SHAN|date=2015-07-02|title=Early Cretaceous vertebrates from the Xinlong Formation of Guangxi (southern China): A review|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/279805233|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=-1|pages=143\u2013159|doi=10.1017/S0016756815000394}}</ref> Buffetaut and Suteethorn suggested that the Xinlong Formation could be related to the Sao Khua or Khok Kruat Formations, since similar types of fossils have been recovered in these regions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|date=1999-06-15|title=The dinosaur fauna of the Sao Khua Formation of Thailand and the beginning of the Cretaceous radiation of dinosaurs in Asia|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018299000048|journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|language=en|volume=150|issue=1\u20132|pages=13\u201323|bibcode=1999PPP...150...13B|doi=10.1016/S0031-0182(99)00004-8|issn=0031-0182}}</ref> Other spinosaurid teeth have been recovered from central China<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/271967379|title=A probable Baryonychine (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) tooth from the Upper Cretaceous of Henan Province, China|last=Hone|first=David|last2=Xu|first2=Xing|date=2010|website=ResearchGate|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-19|last3=Wang|first3=Deyou}}</ref> and [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2014/02/140224204737.htm|title=First discovery of dinosaur fossils in Malaysia|last=|first=|date=2014|access-date=2018-10-25|publisher=ResearchSEA|language=en|via=ScienceDaily}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, an isolated tooth (specimen [[Gunma Museum of Natural History|GMNH]]-PV-999) was found by a fossil prospector in the [[Sebayashi Formation]], Japan. The tooth was believed to belong to a [[marine reptile]] until 2003, when Japanese palaeontologist Yoshikazu Hasegawa and colleagues referred it to ?''Siamosaurus sp.'' (of uncertain species).<ref name=\":4\" /> The tooth came from rocks dated to the Barremian, similar in age to sediments that ''Siamosaurus'' teeth have been recovered from in Thailand.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Hasegawa|first=Y|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Manabe|first3=M|last4=Takakuwa|first4=Yuji|date=2003-03-01|title=A possible spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Gunma, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/313142817|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=7|pages=1\u20135}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> In 2015, a more incomplete tooth was recovered from the same formation by two local children. Kept under the specimen number KDC-PV-0003, the tooth was assigned to an indeterminate spinosaurid in 2017 by Japanese palaeontologist Kubota Katsuhiro and colleagues.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Katsuhiro|first=Kubota|last2=Takakuwa|first2=Yuji|last3=Yoshikazu|first3=Hasegawa|date=2017-03-31|title=Second discovery of a spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Kanna Town, Gunma Prefecture, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/317368894|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=01}}</ref>\n\nThailand's [[Khok Kruat Formation]] assumes a younger ([[Aptian]]; 125 to 113 million years old) age than the Sao Khua Formation,<ref name=\":12\" /> and has provided many spinosaurid teeth, including ones from ''Siamosaurus''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002-09-01|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.miketaylor.org.uk/dino/pubs/svpca2005/SVPCA2005Abstracts.pdf|title=53rd Symposium of Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy|last=Ahlberg|first=P.E.|last2=Blom|first2=H.|last3=Brazeau|first3=M.D.|last4=Anderson|first4=P.|publisher=The Natural History Museum|year=2005|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Khansubha|first4=Sasa-On|last5=Tong|first5=Haiyan|last6=Wongko|first6=K|date=2005-01-01|title=The dinosaur fauna from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) of Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/312976683|journal=Proceedings of the International Conference on Geology, Geotechnology and Mineral Resources of Indochina|pages=575\u2013581}}</ref> Given the varied size and [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]] of the teeth found, the presence of multiple spinosaur taxa in the region is likely.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/252320809|title=Program and Abstracts. 9th Annual Meeting of the European Association of Vertebrate Palaeontologists, Heraklion, Crete, 14-19 June 2011|last=van der Geer|first=Alexandra|last2=Athanassiou|first2=Athanassios|date=2011-01-01}}</ref> In 2004, excavation began on a partial skeleton from an outcrop of the formation near the city of [[Khon Kaen]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|title=52nd Symposium for Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy and the 13th meeting of the Symposium for Palaeontological Preparation and Conservation|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|publisher=University of Leicester & New Walk Museum|year=2004|isbn=|location=Leicester|pages=}}</ref> The material was described by British palaeontologist [[Angela Milner]], Buffetaut, and Suteethorn in 2007, and consists of cervical (neck) and [[Dorsal vertebrae|dorsal]] (back) vertebrae, one {{Convert|60|cm||adj=on}} high [[neural spine]], [[pelvis]] (hip) fragments, and limb bones. The cervical vertebrae and pelvic region resemble those of the European spinosaur ''[[Baryonyx]]'', and the neural spine is elongated similarly to, although not as much as, those of the African genus ''[[Spinosaurus]]''.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Angela|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Suteethorn|first3=Varavudh|date=2007|title=A tall-spined spinosaurid theropod from Thailand and the biogeography of spinosaurs|url=http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Future-Past-Meetings/MeetingPdfs/JVP_07.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume='''27''' (supplement 3)|pages=118A|via=}}</ref> A ''Siamosaurus'' tooth found nearby indicates the skeleton may belong to this genus, though this could also represent a scavenging event.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|displayauthors=etal|date=2004|title=Asian spinosaur confirmed|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|journal=SVPCA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n\nIn 2004, [[Don Lessem]] estimated ''Siamosaurus'' at {{Convert|9.1|m||abbr=}} long.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lessem|first=Don|url=http://archive.org/details/scholasticdinosa00less|title=Scholastic dinosaurs A to Z : the ultimate dinosaur encyclopedia|last2=Sovak|first2=Jan|last3=Scholastic Reference (Firm)|date=2004|publisher=New York : Scholastic|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> In 2005, Sussana Davidson and colleagues gave a lower estimate of {{Convert|8|m||abbr=}} in length and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/usborneinternetl00susa|title=The Usborne Internet-linked World atlas of dinosaurs|last=Davidson|first=Susanna|last2=Turnbull|first2=Stephanie|last3=Firth|first3=Rachel|last4=Rey|first4=Luis V.|last5=Slane|first5=Andrea|last6=Naish|first6=Darren|last7=Martill|first7=David M.|last8=Usborne Publishing Ltd|date=2005|publisher=New York : Scholastic Inc.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> And in 2016, Molina-P\u00e9rez and Larramendi estimated it at approximately {{convert|5.1|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|1.45|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall at the hips and weighing {{convert|255|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite book|last=Molina-Per\u00e9z & Larramendi|title=R\u00e9cords y curiosidades de los dinosaurios Ter\u00f3podos y otros dinosauromorfos|publisher=Larousse|year=2016|isbn=9780565094973|location=Barcelona, Spain|pages=275}}</ref> However, reliable calculations on the weight and body size of fragmentary dinosaurs like ''Siamosaurus'' are hindered by the lack of good material, such as a skull or body fossil.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> \n\n=== Type specimens ===\n[[File:Asian_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Diagram comparing the [[holotype]] tooth (first from left) with other spinosaurid teeth from Asia]]\nFossil theropod teeth are typically identified by attributes such as the proportions, size, and curvature of the [[Crown (tooth)|crown]], as well as the presence and/or shape of the [[Denticle (tooth feature)|denticles]] (serrations).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Joshua B.|last2=Vann|first2=David R.|last3=Dodson|first3=Peter|date=2005|title=Dental morphology and variation in theropod dinosaurs: Implications for the taxonomic identification of isolated teeth|journal=The Anatomical Record Part A: Discoveries in Molecular, Cellular, and Evolutionary Biology|language=en|volume=285A|issue=2|pages=699\u2013736|doi=10.1002/ar.a.20206|pmid=15986487|issn=1552-4884}}</ref> The holotype of ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' (specimen DMR TF 2043a) is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} in total length, with the crown being {{Convert|47.7|mm|}} long, and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm|}} wide at its base. The tooth is relatively straight, with only minor front to back curvature. It is oval in cross section while other specimens are nearly circular in this aspect. Unlike in most theropods, the carinae (edges) of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth lack well-defined serrations. Some teeth (including the holotype) have a wave-like double recurvature when viewed front to back, which Buffetaut and Ingavat compared to that seen in [[Carnosauria|carnosaur]] teeth from the same formation and one ''[[Deinonychus]]'' tooth described by [[John Ostrom]] in 1969. The ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype is symmetrically concave front to back, and bears 15 flutes (lengthwise ridges) on its [[Glossary of dentistry#lingual|lingual]] (the side that faces the tongue) and [[Glossary of dentistry#labial|labial]] (outward facing) surfaces. These flutes run from the base of the crown before stopping {{Convert|5|mm|}} from the rounded tooth tip. A region of the holotype where the [[Tooth enamel|enamel]] (outer layer of the teeth) has weathered away reveals that these flutes extend down to the [[Dentin|dentine]] (second layer of the teeth).<ref name=\":0\" /> The enamel also has a granular (finely wrinkled) texture, as seen in teeth from ''Baryonyx''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2007|title=The spinosaurid dinosaur Baryonyx (Saurischia, Theropoda) in the Early Cretaceous of Portugal|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/geological-magazine/article/spinosaurid-dinosaur-baryonyx-saurischia-theropoda-in-the-early-cretaceous-of-portugal/E2F9B7C099506CE2CD948E022FBDAD5E|journal=Geological Magazine|language=en|volume=144|issue=6|pages=1021\u20131025|doi=10.1017/S0016756807003883|bibcode=2007GeoM..144.1021B|issn=1469-5081|via=}}</ref> Some of the [[Tooth root|root]] is preserved in the holotype and, as in all theropods, there is a large pocket for the tooth [[Pulp (tooth)|pulp]], which would have housed blood vessels and nerves. The holotype is among the larger teeth discovered by Buffetaut and Ingavat, one much smaller specimen (DMR TF 2043b) measures {{Convert|24.3|mm|}} in length. According to the authors, this dramatic size range suggests the teeth are from individuals of different ages.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Possible material ===\n[[File:Siamosaurus.jpg|thumb|Speculative [[Paleoart|restoration]] of ''Siamosaurus'' based on relatives]]\n\nThe first Sebayashi Formation specimen (GMNH-PV-999) is an isolated tooth crown with a partially intact root. It is unknown on which jaw the tooth was positioned nor which surface faced the inside or outside of the mouth. The tooth's front and back carinae are well-defined, though the former is not well preserved. Besides having a broader, {{Convert|20 by 14|mm||adj=on}} wide base and being slightly smaller at {{Convert|51|mm|}} in length, GMNH-PV-999 has a very similar morphology to the ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype. Features shared between the two specimens include: a straight and only slightly compressed shape; a somewhat oval cross section; no serrations on the carinae (possibly due to bad preservation); and a flutes on the crown surface, the Japan specimen having 12 on each side. The specimens also share a crown surface with numerous small granular structures oriented parallel to their lengths. Because of these resemblances, Hasegawa and colleagues regarded GMNH-PV-999 as nearly identical to DMR TF 2043a.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n[[File:Sebayashi_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Partial tooth of an indeterminate spinosaurid (KDC-PV-0003) and possible ''Siamosaurus'' tooth (GMNH-PV-999), in the [[National Museum of Nature and Science]], Tokyo]]\n\nKDC-PV-0003, the second tooth found in the Sebayashi Formation, consists of a slightly recurved crown fragment with a preserved length of {{Convert|10|mm|}}. At its base, the crown is {{Convert|7.4|mm|}} long and {{Convert|6.8|mm|}} wide, with an almost circular cross section. Though less complete than the former specimens, KDC-PV-0003 exhibits better preservation of small details such as visible serrations, although poorly defined ones. The denticles, of which there are two to three every {{Convert|1|mm||adj=on}}, are visible only on the front carinae, due to the rear of the tooth being obscured by rock [[Matrix (geology)|matrix]]. A {{Convert|5.5|mm||adj=on}} long gap at the fossil's base exposes the dentine, which is covered in a {{Convert|1.6|mm||adj=on}} thick layer of enamel. The little that is preserved of KDC-PV-0003 shows that like the first Sebayashi Formation tooth, it has a granular texture and a minimum of 12 flutes on its surface, not all of which stretch to the full length of the crown. The granular structures of KDC-PV-0003 are sharper than in GMNH-PV-999. The interdenticle sulci (tiny furrows near the gaps between each denticle) of KDC-PV-0003 have an [[Oblique angle|oblique]] orientation of 45 degrees, exactly like those seen in GMNH-PV-999.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOut of the four teeth referred to ''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'', specimen [[IVPP]] V 4793 is the most intact, although still somewhat deformed. The crown, which is missing its tip, is {{Convert|69|mm|}} long and {{Convert|16.5 by 13|mm|}} wide at the base. The tooth is straight, only slightly recurved, and has an oval cross section. The front and rear carinae are distinct, though their serrations have been heavily eroded, similar to those of KDC-PV-0003. Like the Thailand and Japan teeth, the ''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'' specimens bear developed flutes and a granular surface. As in both Sebayashi Formation teeth, there are 12 flutes on each face of ''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis''{{'}}s teeth. Like in KDC-PV-0003, thee flutes of varied lengths. Buffetaut and colleagues likened them most to those of ''Siamosaurus'', with respect to their identical crown shape, fluting, and granular enamel.<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />\n\n== Classification ==\n[[File:Spinosaurus_sp_Marocco_Cenom.JPG|thumb|Tooth of the related genus ''[[Spinosaurus]]'', Museo di Storia Naturale A. Stoppani, [[Lombardy]]]]\n\nIn 1986, Buffetaut and Ingavat classified ''Siamosaurus'' as a theropod because of the straight tall crown and double lateral recurvature of its teeth. At the time, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s particular combination of dental characteristics, especially the longitudinal fluting and lack of serrations, had not been observed in other theropods. The authors noted similarities in ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth to those of [[Ceratosauria|ceratosaurian]] tooth crowns, some of which also have longitudinal flutes. However, this identification was ruled out, since ceratosaur teeth differ in cross section, bear far fewer dental flutes, and have distinct serrations. Buffetaut and Suteethorn concluded that the closest taxon in dentition to ''Siamosaurus'' was ''Spinosaurus''. Like ''Siamosaurus,'' this African genus had straight and unserrated conical teeth, and though ''Spinosaurus'' lacked the developed flutes seen in ''Siamosaurus,'' Buffetaut and Ingavat noted that both smooth and fluted spinosaur teeth have been reported from Africa. Therefore, they tentatively placed ''Siamosaurus'' in the Spinosauridae [[Family (biology)|family]], based on close similarities in dentition to ''Spinosaurus aegyptiacus.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nMany palaeontologists have expressed skepticism towards Buffetaut and Ingavat's identification of ''Siamosaurus'', given that spinosaurid teeth, including many from Asia, have been time and again mistaken for those of aquatic reptiles like crocodilians, plesiosaurs, and ichthyosaurs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2010-01-01|title=Spinosaurs before Stromer: early finds of spinosaurid dinosaurs and their interpretations|url=http://sp.lyellcollection.org/content/343/1/175|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|language=en|volume=343|issue=1|pages=175\u2013188|bibcode=2010GSLSP.343..175B|doi=10.1144/SP343.10|issn=0305-8719}}</ref> In view of this, the German palaeontologist [[Hans-Dieter Sues]] and colleagues in 2002 argued that there is not enough material to confidently identify ''Siamosaurus'' as a dinosaur.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sues|first=Hans-Dieter|last2=Frey|first2=Eberhard|last3=Martill|first3=David M.|last4=Scott|first4=Diane M.|date=2002-09-19|title=Irritator challengeri, a spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Brazil|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|language=en|volume=22|issue=3|pages=535\u2013547|doi=10.1671/0272-4634(2002)022[0535:icasdt]2.0.co;2|issn=0272-4634}}</ref> In 2004, American palaeontologist [[Thomas Holtz]] and colleagues considered it a [[nomen dubium|''nomen dubium'']] (dubious name), stating that its teeth might instead belong to contemporaneous fish such as [[saurodontid]] or [[Ichthyodectidae|ichthyodectid]] [[Teleost|teleosts]].<ref name=\"HMC04\">Holtz Jr., T.R., Molnar, R.E., and Currie, P.J. (2004). \"Basal Tetanurae\". In: Weishampel, D.B., Dodson, P., and Osm\u00f3lska, H. (eds.), ''The Dinosauria'' (second edition). Berkeley: University of California Press:Berkeley, p. 71-110. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}</ref> The same year, American palaeontologist [[David Weishampel]] and colleagues placed ''Siamosaurus'' as an indeterminate theropod.<ref>{{Citation|last=Weishampel|first=David|title=Dinosaur Distribution|date=2004-06-12|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/234025996|pages=517\u2013606|access-date=2018-08-28|last2=Le Loeuff|first2=Jean|last3=Coria|first3=Rodolfo|last4=M. P. Gomani|first4=Elizabeth|last5=Zhao|first5=X|last6=Xu|first6=Xing|last7=Barrett|first7=Paul|last8=Sahni|first8=Ashok|last9=Noto|first9=Christopher}}</ref> And in 2012, an analysis by American palaeontologist Matthew Carrano and colleagues agreed with the possibility of confusion with other reptiles, and regarded the genus as a possible indeterminate spinosaur. They pointed out that oftentimes, isolated teeth are an unstable foundation for naming theropod taxa, and most species based on them turn out to be invalid.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Carrano|first=Matthew T.|last2=Benson|first2=Roger B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=Scott D.|date=2012-05-17|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|language=en|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927|issn=1477-2019}}</ref> This problem is especially common with spinosaurs, given that [[Cranium|cranial]] and skeletal fossils from the group are rare.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite journal|last=William Elliott HONE|first=David|last2=Richard HOLTZ|first2=Thomas|date=2017-06-01|title=A Century of Spinosaurs - A Review and Revision of the Spinosauridae with Comments on Their Ecology|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/318228524|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica - English Edition|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Plesiosaur_skull.jpg|thumb|left|Spinosaurid teeth are often mistaken for those of [[plesiosaurs]] (above) and vice versa, though there are certain differences between their dentition]]\n\nSome crocodilians have teeth with flutes similar to those in Asian spinosaurid teeth. However, crocodilian teeth are usually more strongly recurved than spinosaur teeth.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Crocodilians also lack the lateral double recurvature of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s tooth crowns, which, based on their shape, were probably vertically inserted into the jaw, whereas long-snouted crocodilian teeth are usually jut out from the mouth at an angle. Though ''Siamosaurus'' and plesiosaur teeth are similar in overall shape, Buffetaut and Ingavat point out that plesiosaurs have significantly more-recurved tooth crowns.<ref name=\":0\" /> Compared to plesiosaurs, Asian spinosaurid teeth also have coarser and more numerous flutes that extend almost the whole length of the crown.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />''<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2008, Buffetaut and colleagues noted that \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' teeth bear carinae on the plane of the crown's curvature, a condition not observed in plesiosaur teeth. The discovery of the Khok Kruat skeleton and of baryonychine teeth with dental flutes similar to those of ''Siamosaurus'', were also brought up by the researchers as further evidence of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s spinosaurid classification.''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />'' Later discoveries revealed that flutes and a lack of serrations were common characteristics of spinosaurid teeth.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Schultz|first2=Cesar L.|date=2017-11-06|title=Spinosaur taxonomy and evolution of craniodental features: Evidence from Brazil|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=12|issue=11|pages=e0187070|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187070|issn=1932-6203|pmc=5673194|pmid=29107966|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1287070S}}</ref><ref name=\":16\" /> \n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek.jpg|thumb|Restoration of ''[[Ichthyovenator]]'', a [[Spinosaurinae|spinosaurine]] from what is now Laos]]\n\nIn 2017, the Brazilian palaeontologists Marcos Sales and Cesar Schultz accepted ''Siamosaurus'' as a spinosaur, but stated that its teeth and those of ''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'' are too similar to those of other Cretaceous spinosaurids to unequivocally erect new taxa.<ref name=\":17\" /> However, Carrano and colleagues stated that the Khok Kruat skeleton may provide answers to their identification.<ref name=\":6\" /> Authors such as Milner and colleagues,<ref name=\":9\" /> Bertin Tor,<ref name=\":14\" /> Kamonlak Wongko and colleagues,<ref name=\":8\" /> and Thomas Holtz<ref name=\"Holtz2008\">{{cite book|title=Dinosaurs: The Most Complete, Up-to-Date Encyclopedia for Dinosaur Lovers of All Ages|last=Holtz|first=Thomas R. Jr.|date=2011|chapter=Winter 2010 Appendix|chapter-url=http://www.geol.umd.edu/~tholtz/dinoappendix/HoltzappendixWinter2010.pdf}}</ref> regarded the skeleton as first irrefutable evidence of spinosaurs in Asia. Nevertheless, in 2012 Ronan Allain and colleagues described the Laos spinosaurid ''[[Ichthyovenator]]'' and dubbed it \"The first definitive Asian spinosaurid\".<ref name=\"AXRK12\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref> Mickey Mortimer pointed out shortly after that even discounting teeth, the Khok Kruat skeleton was first mentioned eight years prior to ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s description.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dml.cmnh.org/2012Apr/msg00480.html|title=RE: Ichthyovenator, new spinosaurid from Early Cretaceous of Laos|website=dml.cmnh.org|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref> Sales and Shultz suggested that the various Asian teeth might eventually be attributed to ''Ichthyovenator''-like forms.<ref name=\":17\" /> In a 2014 abstract, Allain announced that three teeth from ''Ichthyovenator'' had been discovered, which typically of spinosaurines, bore straight and unserrated crowns. Though no comparison was made to the other Asian teeth.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Allain|first=Ronan|date=2014|title=New material of the theropod Ichthyovenator from Ban Kalum type locality (Laos): Implications for the synonymy of Spinosaurus and Sigilmassasaurus and the phylogeny of Spinosauridae|url=http://vertpaleo.org/GlobalPDFS/SVP-2014-Program-and-Abstract-Book-9-18-2014.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology Programs and Abstracts|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nSpinosaurids were large [[Bipedalism|bipedal]] [[Carnivore|carnivores]] with well-built forelimbs and elongated, crocodile-like skulls. The [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] and [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] affinities of the group are subject to active research and debate, given that in comparison to other theropod groups, many of the family's taxa are based on poor fossil material.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Traditionally, the group is split into the [[subfamilies]] Spinosaurinae (unserrated, straight teeth with well marked flutes and a circular cross section) and Baryonychinae (finely serrated, somewhat recurved teeth with weaker flutes and a more oval cross section). The morphological variation seen in spinosaurid teeth, however, shows that these characteristics are not always consistent within the subfamilies.<ref name=\":19\" /> The exact position of ''Siamosaurus'' within the Spinosauridae is difficulty to determine because of its fragmentary nature, problems in classifying the many Asian spinosaur teeth stem from the lack of associated skulls or skeletons.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002-09-01|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409}}</ref> Asian spinosaurid teeth show characteristics from both Spinosaurinae and Baryonychinae, such as how KDC-PV-0003 shares irregularly sized mesial serrations with the latter group.<ref name=\":5\" /> In 2010, the British palaeontologist David Hone and colleagues referred ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' to the Spinosaurinae.<ref name=\":19\" /> Likewise, British palaeontologist Thomas Arden and colleagues resolved ''Siamosaurus'' as a basal member of the Spinosaurinae in 2019, their [[cladogram]] can be seen below.<ref name=\"arden2018\">{{cite journal|last=Arden|first=T.M.S.|last2=Klein|first2=C.G.|last3=Zouhri|first3=S.|last4=Longrich|first4=N.R.|date=|year=2019|title=Aquatic adaptation in the skull of carnivorous dinosaurs (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) and the evolution of aquatic habits in ''Spinosaurus''|url=|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=93|pages=275\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2018.06.013|via=}}</ref>\n\n{{clade|{{clade\n |1=Praia das Aguncheiras taxon\n |label2=[[Baryonychinae]]\n |2={{clade\n  |1=''[[Baryonyx walkeri]]'' [[File:Baryonyx_walkeri_restoration.jpg|middle|80px]]\n  |2=''[[Suchomimus tenerensis]]'' [[File:Suchomimustenerensis_(Flipped).png|middle|80px]] }}\n |label3=[[Spinosaurinae]]\n |3={{clade\n  |1='''''Siamosaurus suteethorni'''''\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=Eumeralla taxon\n   |2={{clade\n    |1=''[[Ichthyovenator laosensis]]'' [[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek_(Flipped).jpg|middle|77px]]\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Irritator challengeri]]'' [[File:Irritator Life Reconstruction.jpg|middle|80 px]]\n     |2=''[[Oxalaia quilombensis]]''\n     |label3=[[Spinosaurini]]\n     |3={{clade\n      |1=Gara Samani taxon\n      |2=''[[Sigilmassasaurus brevicollis]]''\n      |3=''[[Spinosaurus aegyptiacus]]'' [[File:Spinosaurus by Joschua Kn\u00fcppe.png|middle|80 px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}|style=font-size: 85%; line-height:85%;|label1=[[Spinosauridae]]}}\n\n==Palaeobiology==\n\n=== Diet and feeding ===\nBuffetaut and Ingavat suggested in 1986 that ''Siamosaurus'', like other spinosaurids, probably led a heavily [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) lifestyle. Spinosaurids had highly specialised teeth better suited for piercing rather than tearing flesh, thanks to their long, conical tooth crowns with reduced or absent serrations. This dental morphology is also seen in plesiosaurs and long-snouted crocodilians.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\">{{Cite journal|last=Hone|first=David William Elliott|last2=Holtz|first2=Thomas Richard|date=June 2017|title=A century of spinosaurs \u2013 a review and revision of the Spinosauridae with comments on their ecology|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica \u2013 English Edition|language=en|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328|issn=1000-9515}}</ref> Though skull material from ''Siamosaurus'' is lacking, spinosaurs are known to have had low, narrow and elongated jaws with snout tips that fanned out into a [[Rosette (design)|rosette]]-like shape, similar to that of modern [[Gharial]]<nowiki/>s.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Fossil evidence shows that besides fish, spinosaurids also consumed pterosaurs and other dinosaurs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Martill|first2=David|last3=Escuilli\u00e9|first3=Fran\u00e7ois|date=2004-07-01|title=Pterosaurs as part of a spinosaur diet|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/430033a|journal=Nature|language=En|volume=429|issue=6995|pages=33|doi=10.1038/430033a|pmid=15229562|bibcode=2004Natur.429...33B|issn=0028-0836}}</ref> In the Sao Khua Formation, localities such as Wat Sakawan have yielded sauropod remains in association with tooth crowns from ''Siamosaurus'', documenting either predation or scavenging on part of the latter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n[[File:Spinosaurid_and_Kinnareemimus.PNG|thumb|Restoration of a generic spinosaur feeding on a [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] carcass in the [[Sao Khua Formation]] (''[[Kinnareemimus]]'' in the background), based on teeth belonging to ''Siamosaurus''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Lacerda|first2=Marcel B.|last3=Horn|first3=Bruno L. D.|last4=Oliveira|first4=Isabel A. P. de|last5=Schultz|first5=Cesar L.|date=2016-02-01|title=The \"\u03c7\" of the Matter: Testing the Relationship between Paleoenvironments and Three Theropod Clades|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=11|issue=2|pages=e0147031|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147031|pmid=26829315|pmc=4734717|issn=1932-6203|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147031S}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2006, Thai biologist Komsorn Lauprasert examined fossils collected from the Phu Kradung, Sao Khua, and Khok Kruat Formations. In this study, the teeth of ''Siamosaurus'' and a Morrocan spinosaurid were compared to those of crocodilians using [[Scanning electron microscope|scanning electron microscopy]]. Lauprasert found that spinosaurids and crocodilians may have employed similar feeding tactics and been under comparable [[Constraint (classical mechanics)|mechanical constraints]], based on resemblances in the [[microstructure]] of their tooth enamel. Lauprasert suggested that ''Siamosaurus'' could have therefore replaced the [[ecological niche]] of contemporaneous long-snouted crocodilians as a piscivorous predator. He notes that this likely occured in correlation with the rising aridity of the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations during the Early Cretaceous, since ''Siamosaurus'' had better mobility in a dry environment than crocodilians did. This could explain the absence of long-snouted crocodilian fossils from that time and place.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite thesis|last=Lauprasert|first=Komsorn|title=Evolution and palaeoecology of crocodiles in the mesozoic of Khorat plateau, Thailand|date=2006|publisher=Chulalongkorn University|url=https://cuir.car.chula.ac.th/handle/123456789/14411|language=en}}</ref> A similar scenario was proposed for spinosaurids by Hone and colleagues in 2010, who noted that, compared to large crocodilians and obligate aquatic predators, they could more easily travel from one body of water to another in search for prey.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n=== Aquatic habits ===\n\nA 2010 publication by French palaeontologist Romain Amiot and colleagues found that the [[isotopes of oxygen|oxygen isotope]] ratios of spinosaurid bones indicated [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles. Isotope ratios of spinosaurid teeth from various localities, including Thailand and China, were compared with isotopic compositions from contemporaneous theropods, turtles, and crocodilians. The study revealed that, among theropods, spinosaurid isotope ratios were closer to those of turtles and crocodilians. Thai spinosaurid teeth tended to have the largest difference from the ratios of other theropods, and those from Morocco tended to have the least difference. The authors concluded that spinosaurids, like modern crocodilians and hippopotamuses, spent much of their daily lives in or near water. They also suggested that semiaquatic habits and piscivory may explain how spinosaurids coexisted with other large theropods; by feeding on different prey items and occupying a distinct ecological niche, the different types of theropods would have been out of direct competition.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\"RMetal10\">{{cite journal |last=Amiot |first=R. |author2=Buffetaut, E. |author3=L\u00e9cuyer, C. |author4=Wang, X. |author5=Boudad, L. |author6=Ding, Z. |author7=Fourel, F. |author8=Hutt, S. |author9=Martineau, F. |author10=Medeiros, A. |author11=Mo, J. |author12=Simon, L. |author13=Suteethorn, V. |author14=Sweetman, S. |author15=Tong, H. |author16=Zhang, F. |author17=Zhou, Z. |year=2010 |title=Oxygen isotope evidence for semi-aquatic habits among spinosaurid theropods |journal=Geology |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=139\u2013142 |doi=10.1130/G30402.1|bibcode=2010Geo....38..139A }}</ref>\n\n== Palaeoenvironment and palaeobiogeography ==\n[[File:Sao_Khua_Formation_V2.png|thumb|left|Restoration of ''Siamosaurus'' hunting fish in the Sao Khua Formation, with a herd of ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]]'' in the background]]\n\nThe sediments of the Sao Khua Formation, composed of [[Red clay|red clays]], [[Mudstone|mudstones]], [[Sandstone|sandstones]], [[Siltstone|siltstones]] and [[Conglomerate (geology)|conglomerate]] rocks, record a [[fluvial]] environment dominated by lakes, [[Floodplain|floodplains]], and meandering low-energy rivers.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> This is consistent with the types of vertebrate fauna present in the formation, which comprise only terrestrial or freshwater animals, including dinosaurs, turtles, freshwater [[hybodont sharks]] and [[Actinopterygii|actinopterygian]] fishes, and the freshwater crocodilian ''[[Sunosuchus]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> Besides ''Siamosaurus'', there were dinosaurs like the [[Metriacanthosauridae|metriacanthosaurid]] ''Siamotyrannus isanensis'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carrano|first1=M. T.|last2=Benson|first2=R. B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=S. D.|date=2012|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927}}</ref> the [[Ornithomimosauria|ornithomimosaur]] ''[[Kinnareemimus]] khonkaenensis'',<ref name=\"description\">Buffetaut, E., Suteethorn, V. and Tong, H. (2009). \"An early 'ostrich dinosaur' (Theropoda: Ornithomimosauria) from the Early Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of NE Thailand\", pp. 229-243 IN E. Buffetaut, G. Cuny, J. Le Loeuff & V. Suteethorn (eds.), ''Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Ecosystems in SE Asia''. Geological Society, London, Special Publications 315: 229-243. {{doi|10.1144/SP315.16}}</ref> the [[Megaraptora|megaraptoran]] ''[[Phuwiangvenator]]'' ''yaemniyomi'', the basal [[Coelurosauria|coelurosaur]] ''[[Vayuraptor]]'' ''nongbualamphuensis,<ref name=\"Samathietal2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=A.|last2=Chanthasit|first2=P.|last3=Martin Sander|first3=P.|date=May 2019|title=Two new basal coelurosaurian theropod dinosaurs from the Lower Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of Thailand|journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica|language=en|volume=64|issue=2|pages=239\u2013260|doi=10.4202/app.00540.2018}}</ref>'' a ''[[Compsognathus]]''-like theropod, as well as sauropods like ''Phuwiangosaurus sirindhornae'' and two indeterminate forms. Sauropod remains are some of the most abundant in the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> No [[Ornithischia|ornithischian]] dinosaur fossils have been found in the Sao Khua Formation, possibly suggesting that they were uncommon compared to [[Saurischia|saurischian]] dinosaurs.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations had a more [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] climate than the older, more humid [[Phu Kradung Formation]].<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe Khok Kruat Formation is composed mostly of sandstones, conglomerates, siltstones, and [[Shale|shales]]. Similarly to the Sao Khua Formation, the deposition of these sediments occurred in an arid to semi-arid floodplain environment of slow-moving, meandering rivers.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=Jintasakul|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|last4=You|first4=Hai-Lu|date=2015-12-30|title=A New Basal Hadrosauroid Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation in Nakhon Ratchasima Province, Northeastern Thailand|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=10|issue=12|pages=e0145904|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0145904|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4696827|pmid=26716981|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1045904S}}</ref> Vertebrates from the Khok Kruat assemblage include [[Semionotiformes|semionotiform]] fishes, hybodont sharks, turtles, dinosaurs, pterosaurs, and crocodilians. The dinosaur fauna of this ecosystem included the [[Carcharodontosauridae|carcharodontosaurid]] ''[[Siamraptor]]'' ''suwati'',''<ref name=\"Chokchaloemwong2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Chokchaloemwong|first=Duangsuda|last2=Hattori|first2=Soki|last3=Cuesta|first3=Elena|last4=Jintasakul|first4=Pratueng|last5=Shibata|first5=Masateru|last6=Azuma|first6=Yoichi|date=2019-10-09|editor-last=Liu|editor-first=Jun|title=A new carcharodontosaurian theropod (Dinosauria: Saurischia) from the Lower Cretaceous of Thailand|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=14|issue=10|pages=e0222489|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0222489|pmid=31596853|pmc=6784982|issn=1932-6203}}</ref>'' [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontians]] like ''[[Sirindhorna]] khoratensis'',<ref name=\":15\" /> ''[[Ratchasimasaurus]] suranaerae'',<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=JINTASAKUL|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|date=2011-10-01|title=A New Iguanodontian Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation, Nakhon Ratchasima in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/264655916|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica|volume=85|issue=5|pages=969\u2013976|doi=10.1111/j.1755-6724.2011.00530.x}}</ref> and ''[[Siamodon]] nimngami'';<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2011-01-01|title=A new iguanodontian dinosaur from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous, Aptian) of northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396911000425|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|language=en|volume=97|issue=1\u20132|pages=51\u201362|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2011.08.001|issn=0753-3969|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh}}</ref> as well as a ''Phuwiangosaurus''-like sauropod,<ref name=\":7\" /> an indeterminate [[Ceratopsia|ceratopsian]],<ref name=\"sereno2010\">{{cite book|title=New Perspectives on Horned Dinosaurs: The Royal Tyrrell Museum Ceratopsian Symposium|last=Sereno|first=Paul C.|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2010|editor1-last=Ryan|editor1-first=Michael J.|location=Bloomington and Indianapolis|pages=21\u201358|chapter=Taxonomy, cranial morphology, and relationships of parrot-beaked dinosaurs (Ceratopsia:''Psittacosaurus'')|editor2-last=Chinnery-Allgeier|editor2-first=Brenda J.|editor3-last=Eberth|editor3-first=David A.}}</ref> and various indeterminate theropods.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> The formation is probably equivalent to the [[Gres superieurs Formation]] of Laos, since animals like advanced iguanodontians, sauropods, and spinosaurids have also been found there.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\nIn 2010, American palaeontologist [[Stephen L. Brusatte|Stephen Brusatte]] and colleagues noted that the discovery of spinosaurids in Asia, a family previously known only from Europe, Africa, and South America, suggests faunal interchange between the [[Supercontinent|supercontinents]] [[Laurasia]] (in the north) and [[Gondwana]] (in the south) during the early Late Cretaceous. Though it may also be possible that spinosaurids already had a [[cosmopolitan distribution]] before the Middle Cretaceous, and thus preceding the breakup of Laurasia from Gondwana. However, the authors noted that more evidence is needed to test this hypothesis.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Brusatte|first=Stephen|last2=B. J. Benson|first2=R|last3=Xu|first3=Xing|date=2010-12-10|title=The evolution of large-bodied therood dinosaurs during the Mesozoic in Asia|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260714806|journal=Journal of Iberian Geology|volume=36|issue=2|pages=275\u2013296|doi=10.5209/rev_JIGE.2010.v36.n2.12}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n{{Megalosauroidea}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q134636}}\n\n[[Category:Spinosaurids]]\n[[Category:Barremian life]]\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1986]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by \u00c9ric Buffetaut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], ([[Barremian]]) {{Fossilrange|130|125}}\n| image = Siamosaurus_tooth_by_PaleoGeek.png\n| image_caption = Illustrated [[holotype]] tooth, with [[Penny (British decimal coin)|British penny]] for scale\n| taxon = Siamosaurus\n| authority = Buffetaut & Ingavat, 1986\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = *'''''S. suteethorni''''' <small>Buffetaut & Ingavat, 1986 ([[type species|type]])</small>\n| synonyms = *'''''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'''''? <small>Hou, Yeh & Zhao, 1975</small>\n}}\n'''''Siamosaurus''''' (meaning \"Siamese lizard\") is a potentially [[Dubious name|dubious]] [[genus]] of [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived 130 to 113 million years ago, during the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Period (geologic time)|Period]] of what is now [[Isan|northeastern]] [[Thailand]]. It is the first spinosaurid reported from Asia and is known only from tooth [[Fossil|fossils]]; the first of which were found in the [[Sao Khua Formation]], with more teeth later recovered from the younger [[Khok Kruat Formation]]. The [[type species]] '''''Siamosaurus suteethorni''''', whose name honours the Thai [[palaeontologist]] [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], was formally described in [[1986 in paleontology|1986]]. One tooth possibly belonging to the genus was discovered in the Japanese [[Sebayashi Formation]] in 1994, and a tooth similar to it was found at the same site in 2015. In 2009, four teeth from China's [[Xinlong Formation]] were assigned to the spinosaurid species '''''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis''''', which may be the same animal as ''Siamosaurus''. Most of the aforementioned teeth were originally attributed to [[Marine reptile|marine reptiles]]. A partial spinosaurid skeleton from the Khok Kruat Formation was described in 2007, but whether it belongs to ''Siamosaurus'' or not is unclear.\n\nThe [[holotype]] tooth is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} long and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm|}} wide at the base. Since it is a tooth taxon, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s body size and weight are uncertain, though it has been estimated at between {{Convert|5.1 to 9.1|m||abbr=}} and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}. ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s teeth were straight, oval to circular in cross section, and lined with distinct lengthwise ridges. The tooth's [[Tooth enamel|enamel]] was wrinkled, similar to that of teeth from the related genus ''[[Baryonyx]]''. ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s identity has been questioned by many palaeontologists, who argue that its teeth are too similar to those of contemporaneous aquatic reptiles for it to be confidently classed as a dinosaur. Other researchers, who agree that the teeth are spinosaur in origin, deem them too similar to those of other Early Cretaceous spinosaurs to unequivocally raise a new genus. Based on characteristics of its teeth, ''Siamosaurus'' has been placed within the [[Spinosaurinae]] [[subfamily]].\n\nLike all spinosaurids, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth were conical, with reduced or absent [[Serration|serrations]]. This made them suitable for impaling rather than tearing flesh, a trait typically seen in largely [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) animals. Its relatives are known to have also consumed [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]] and small to medium-sized dinosaurs, and there is fossil evidence of ''Siamosaurus'' eating [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] dinosaurs, either via scavenging or hunting. ''Siamosaurus'' lived in a [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] habitat of [[Floodplain|floodplains]] and meandering rivers, where it coexisted with other theropod, sauropod, and (in at least the Khok Kruat Formation) [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontian]] dinosaurs. [[Isotope analysis]] indicates spinosaurids may have had [[semiaquatic]] habits, and ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s role as a piscivorous predator might have reduced the prominence of contemporaneous aquatic reptiles.\n\n== History of discovery ==\n[[File:Cretaceous_strata_in_northeast_and_southeastern_Thailand.png|thumb|left|Geological map of the [[Khorat Plateau]] in northeast Thailand]]\n\nThe [[Sao Khua Formation]], where the first ''Siamosaurus'' [[Fossil|fossils]] were discovered, is part of the [[Khorat Group]].<ref name=\":0\">Buffetaut, E.; and Ingevat, R. (1986). Unusual theropod dinosaur teeth from the Upper Jurassic of Phu Wiang, northeastern Thailand. Rev. Paleobiol. 5: 217-220.</ref> The formation is dated to the [[Barremian]] [[Stage (geology)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Geological period|Period]], 130 to 125 million years ago,<ref name=\":15\" /> though it was formerly believed to be [[Late Jurassic]] in age.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Racey|first=Andrew|last2=G. S. Goodall|first2=J|date=2009-05-12|title=Palynology and stratigraphy of the Mesozoic Khorat Group red bed sequences from Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/249552008|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|volume=315|issue=1|pages=69\u201383|citeseerx=10.1.1.1030.8425|doi=10.1144/SP315.6|bibcode=2009GSLSP.315...69R}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|last=Bertin|first=Tor|date=2010-12-08|title=A catalogue of material and review of the Spinosauridae|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/235679976|journal=PalArch's Journal of Vertebrate Palaeontology|volume=7}}</ref> Out of all [[Mesozoic]] formations in northeastern Thailand, the Sao Khua is the most abundant and diversified in [[vertebrate]] fossil discoveries.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> The Khorat Group exhibits taxa only of continental origin, with no definitive evidence for marine fossils or [[Sedimentary rock|sedimentary]] structures found so far. In 1963, Yoshitsugu Kobayashi of the [[Hokkaido University]] reported ichthyosaur and [[Plesiosauria|plesiosaur]] teeth from the Sao Khua Formation, but these have now been identified as belonging to ''Siamosaurus'' and a [[Crocodilia|crocodilian]] respectively.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/books/book/1678/late-palaeozoic-and-mesozoic-continental|title=Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Continental Ecosystems in SE Asia {{!}} GeoScienceWorld Books {{!}} GeoScienceWorld|website=pubs.geoscienceworld.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, French [[Paleontologists|palaeontologist]] [[Eric Buffetaut|\u00c9ric Buffetaut]] and his Thai colleague Rucha Ingavat described a set of fossil teeth recovered from the Phu Pratu Teema locality of the Sao Khua Formation, in [[Khon Kaen Province]]. They reached no conclusion as to what animal they originated from, their opinion being that the specimens belonged \"either to an unusual [[Theropoda|theropod]] [[dinosaur]], or to some unknown crocodilian\". In [[1986 in paleontology|1986]], a reassessment of the remains by the same authors attributed them to a new [[genus]] and [[species]] of [[spinosaurid]] theropod, which they named ''Siamosaurus suteethorni''. The generic name alludes to the ancient name of Thailand, \"Siam\", while the specific name honours Thai [[geologist]] and palaeontologist [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], and his contributions to vertebrate palaeontology discoveries in Thailand.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:Museum_Dinosaur_KK.jpg|thumb|The [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]] houses [[fossil]] replicas and a sculpture of ''Siamosaurus''<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Boonchai|first=N|last2=Grote|first2=Paul|last3=Jintasakul|first3=P|date=2009-01-01|title=Paleontological parks and museums and prominent fossil sites in Thailand and their importance in the conservation of fossils|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/286206751|journal=PaleoParks - the Protection and Conservation of Fossil Sites Worldwide|pages=75\u201395}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1264683/centre-of-the-northeast|title=Centre of the Northeast|last=Karnjanatawe|first=Karnjana|date=June 2017|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23}}</ref>]]\n\nThe best-preserved specimen from the series, designated DMR TF 2043a, was chosen as the [[holotype]] of ''Siamosaurus.<ref name=\":0\" />'' The [[Paratype|paratypes]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Siamosaurussuteethorni|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=Mickey|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> comprise eight other well-preserved teeth catalogued as DMR TF 2043b to i. The original fossils are currently housed in the palaeontological collection of the [[Department of Mineral Resources (Thailand)|Department of Mineral Resources]], [[Bangkok]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Other fossils later referred to the genus, including two well preserved teeth (SM2016-1-147 and SM2016-1-165) and one [[Cervical vertebrae|cervical]] (neck) [[vertebra]] (SM2016-1-067) are stored in the [[Sirindhorn Museum]], [[Kalasin Province]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219641|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219713|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219621|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> Isolated ''Siamosaurus'' teeth are common in the Sao Khua Formation.<ref name=\":1\" /> Large hypothetical sculptures of the animal have been erected in various places across northeast Thailand, including Si Wiang Dinosaur Park,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1137381/jurassic-park-vs-the-weekend-warrior|title=Jurassic Park vs the weekend warrior|last=Mekloy|first=Pongpet|date=November 2016|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23}}</ref> the [[Siam Paragon]] shopping mall in Bangkok,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/formerly-one-of-the-biggest-smiles-in-the-land-of-smiles|title=Formerly one of the biggest smiles in the Land of Smiles|last=hermes|first=|date=2017-05-04|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-08-23|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/life/Dinosaurs-in-the-big-city-30273487.html|title=Dinosaurs in the big city - The Nation|work=The Nation|access-date=2018-08-23|language=en}}</ref> and the [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]].<ref name=\":10\" /> The animal was also illustrated on Thai postage stamps released in 1997, along with fellow Thai dinosaurs ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]] sirindhornae,'' ''[[Siamotyrannus]] isanensis'', and ''[[Psittacosaurus]] sattayaraki''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/scott2002standar00scot_1|title=Scott 2002 standard postage stamp catalogue. Volume 6 : countries of the world, So-Z|last=Scott Publishing Co|date=2001|publisher=Sidney, OH : Scott Pub. Co.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Khok_Kruat_spinosaurid_neural_spine.png|thumb|left|upright=0.60|Illustrated [[neural spine]] of a [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] from the [[Khok Kruat Formation]]]]\n\n''Siamosaurus'' is the first reported spinosaurid dinosaur from Asia,<ref name=\":14\" /> and subsequently to its naming, material resembling or possibly belonging to the taxon has been found across the continent. In 1975, Chinese palaeontologist Hou Lian-Hai and colleagues described five teeth as a new species of the [[Pliosauroidea|pliosauroid]] ''[[Sinopliosaurus]]'', which they named ''S. fusuiensis''.<ref>Hou, L., Yeh, H. and Zhao, X. (1975). Fossil reptiles from Fusui, Kwangshi. ''Vertebrata PalAsiatica'' 13; 24-33</ref> Four of these teeth (one was not found in the museum collection) were reassigned by Buffetaut and colleagues in 2008 to a ''Siamosaurus''-like taxon and referred to as [[\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis|\"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'']]''.'' The researchers deemed \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' as \"closely related to, if not identical with\" ''Siamosaurus suteethorni.<ref name=\"EBetal082\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360}}</ref>'' American palaeontologist Mickey Mortimer informally placed \"''S.''\" ''fusuiensis'' under the latter genus as a tentative additional species, ''Siamosaurus fusuiensis'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Sinopliosaurusfusuiensis|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=M.|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref> an analysis also held by Spanish palaeontologists Rub\u00e9n Molina-P\u00e9rez and Asier Larramendi in 2016.''<ref name=\":20\" />'' In 2019, it was referred by Thai palaeontologist Wongko Kamonlak and colleagues as the \"Chinese ''Siamosaurus''\".''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wongko|first=Kamonlak|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Khamha|first3=Suchada|last4=Lauprasert|first4=Komsorn|date=2019-03-31|title=Spinosaurid theropod teeth from the Red Beds of the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://li01.tci-thaijo.org/index.php/tnh/article/view/181194|journal=Tropical Natural History|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=8\u201320|issn=2586-9892}}</ref>'' The original specimens were collected from China's Early Cretaceous [[Xinlong Formation]], in which indeterminate spinosaurs are frequently reported, though most of them are hard to differentiate from those of Japan or Thailand without further fossil material besides teeth''.''<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite journal|last=MO|first=JINYOU|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|last4=Amiot|first4=Romain|last5=Cavin|first5=Lionel|last6=Cuny|first6=Gilles|last7=Suteethorn|first7=Varavudh|last8=SUTEETHORN|first8=SURAVECH|last9=JIANG|first9=SHAN|date=2015-07-02|title=Early Cretaceous vertebrates from the Xinlong Formation of Guangxi (southern China): A review|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/279805233|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=-1|pages=143\u2013159|doi=10.1017/S0016756815000394}}</ref> Buffetaut and Suteethorn suggested that the Xinlong Formation could be related to the Sao Khua or Khok Kruat Formations, since similar types of fossils have been recovered in these regions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|date=1999-06-15|title=The dinosaur fauna of the Sao Khua Formation of Thailand and the beginning of the Cretaceous radiation of dinosaurs in Asia|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018299000048|journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|language=en|volume=150|issue=1\u20132|pages=13\u201323|bibcode=1999PPP...150...13B|doi=10.1016/S0031-0182(99)00004-8|issn=0031-0182}}</ref> Other spinosaurid teeth have been recovered from central China<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/271967379|title=A probable Baryonychine (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) tooth from the Upper Cretaceous of Henan Province, China|last=Hone|first=David|last2=Xu|first2=Xing|date=2010|website=ResearchGate|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-19|last3=Wang|first3=Deyou}}</ref> and [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2014/02/140224204737.htm|title=First discovery of dinosaur fossils in Malaysia|last=|first=|date=2014|access-date=2018-10-25|publisher=ResearchSEA|language=en|via=ScienceDaily}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, an isolated tooth (specimen [[Gunma Museum of Natural History|GMNH]]-PV-999) was found by a fossil prospector in the [[Sebayashi Formation]], Japan. The tooth was believed to belong to a [[marine reptile]] until 2003, when Japanese palaeontologist Yoshikazu Hasegawa and colleagues referred it to ?''Siamosaurus sp.'' (of uncertain species).<ref name=\":4\" /> The tooth came from rocks dated to the Barremian, similar in age to sediments that ''Siamosaurus'' teeth have been recovered from in Thailand.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Hasegawa|first=Y|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Manabe|first3=M|last4=Takakuwa|first4=Yuji|date=2003-03-01|title=A possible spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Gunma, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/313142817|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=7|pages=1\u20135}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> In 2015, a more incomplete tooth was recovered from the same formation by two local children. Kept under the specimen number KDC-PV-0003, the tooth was assigned to an indeterminate spinosaurid in 2017 by Japanese palaeontologist Kubota Katsuhiro and colleagues.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Katsuhiro|first=Kubota|last2=Takakuwa|first2=Yuji|last3=Yoshikazu|first3=Hasegawa|date=2017-03-31|title=Second discovery of a spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Kanna Town, Gunma Prefecture, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/317368894|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=01}}</ref>\n\nThailand's [[Khok Kruat Formation]] assumes a younger ([[Aptian]]; 125 to 113 million years old) age than the Sao Khua Formation,<ref name=\":12\" /> and has provided many spinosaurid teeth, including ones from ''Siamosaurus''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002-09-01|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.miketaylor.org.uk/dino/pubs/svpca2005/SVPCA2005Abstracts.pdf|title=53rd Symposium of Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy|last=Ahlberg|first=P.E.|last2=Blom|first2=H.|last3=Brazeau|first3=M.D.|last4=Anderson|first4=P.|publisher=The Natural History Museum|year=2005|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Khansubha|first4=Sasa-On|last5=Tong|first5=Haiyan|last6=Wongko|first6=K|date=2005-01-01|title=The dinosaur fauna from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) of Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/312976683|journal=Proceedings of the International Conference on Geology, Geotechnology and Mineral Resources of Indochina|pages=575\u2013581}}</ref> Given the varied size and [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]] of the teeth found, the presence of multiple spinosaur taxa in the region is likely.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/252320809|title=Program and Abstracts. 9th Annual Meeting of the European Association of Vertebrate Palaeontologists, Heraklion, Crete, 14-19 June 2011|last=van der Geer|first=Alexandra|last2=Athanassiou|first2=Athanassios|date=2011-01-01}}</ref> In 2004, excavation began on a partial skeleton from an outcrop of the formation near the city of [[Khon Kaen]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|title=52nd Symposium for Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy and the 13th meeting of the Symposium for Palaeontological Preparation and Conservation|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|publisher=University of Leicester & New Walk Museum|year=2004|isbn=|location=Leicester|pages=}}</ref> The material was described by British palaeontologist [[Angela Milner]], Buffetaut, and Suteethorn in 2007, and consists of cervical (neck) and [[Dorsal vertebrae|dorsal]] (back) vertebrae, one {{Convert|60|cm||adj=on}} high [[neural spine]], [[pelvis]] (hip) fragments, and limb bones. The cervical vertebrae and pelvic region resemble those of the European spinosaur ''[[Baryonyx]]'', and the neural spine is elongated similarly to, although not as much as, those of the African genus ''[[Spinosaurus]]''.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Angela|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Suteethorn|first3=Varavudh|date=2007|title=A tall-spined spinosaurid theropod from Thailand and the biogeography of spinosaurs|url=http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Future-Past-Meetings/MeetingPdfs/JVP_07.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume='''27''' (supplement 3)|pages=118A|via=}}</ref> A ''Siamosaurus'' tooth found nearby indicates the skeleton may belong to this genus, though this could also represent a scavenging event.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|displayauthors=etal|date=2004|title=Asian spinosaur confirmed|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|journal=SVPCA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n\nIn 2004, [[Don Lessem]] estimated ''Siamosaurus'' at {{Convert|9.1|m||abbr=}} long.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lessem|first=Don|url=http://archive.org/details/scholasticdinosa00less|title=Scholastic dinosaurs A to Z : the ultimate dinosaur encyclopedia|last2=Sovak|first2=Jan|last3=Scholastic Reference (Firm)|date=2004|publisher=New York : Scholastic|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> In 2005, Sussana Davidson and colleagues gave a lower estimate of {{Convert|8|m||abbr=}} in length and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/usborneinternetl00susa|title=The Usborne Internet-linked World atlas of dinosaurs|last=Davidson|first=Susanna|last2=Turnbull|first2=Stephanie|last3=Firth|first3=Rachel|last4=Rey|first4=Luis V.|last5=Slane|first5=Andrea|last6=Naish|first6=Darren|last7=Martill|first7=David M.|last8=Usborne Publishing Ltd|date=2005|publisher=New York : Scholastic Inc.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> And in 2016, Molina-P\u00e9rez and Larramendi estimated it at approximately {{convert|5.1|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|1.45|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall at the hips and weighing {{convert|255|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite book|last=Molina-Per\u00e9z & Larramendi|title=R\u00e9cords y curiosidades de los dinosaurios Ter\u00f3podos y otros dinosauromorfos|publisher=Larousse|year=2016|isbn=9780565094973|location=Barcelona, Spain|pages=275}}</ref> However, reliable calculations on the weight and body size of fragmentary dinosaurs like ''Siamosaurus'' are hindered by the lack of good material, such as a skull or body fossil.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> \n\n=== Type specimens ===\n[[File:Asian_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Diagram comparing the [[holotype]] tooth (first from left) with other spinosaurid teeth from Asia]]\nFossil theropod teeth are typically identified by attributes such as the proportions, size, and curvature of the [[Crown (tooth)|crown]], as well as the presence and/or shape of the [[Denticle (tooth feature)|denticles]] (serrations).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Joshua B.|last2=Vann|first2=David R.|last3=Dodson|first3=Peter|date=2005|title=Dental morphology and variation in theropod dinosaurs: Implications for the taxonomic identification of isolated teeth|journal=The Anatomical Record Part A: Discoveries in Molecular, Cellular, and Evolutionary Biology|language=en|volume=285A|issue=2|pages=699\u2013736|doi=10.1002/ar.a.20206|pmid=15986487|issn=1552-4884}}</ref> The holotype of ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' (specimen DMR TF 2043a) is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} in total length, with the crown being {{Convert|47.7|mm|}} long, and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm|}} wide at its base. The tooth is relatively straight, with only minor front to back curvature. It is oval in cross section while other specimens are nearly circular in this aspect. Unlike in most theropods, the carinae (edges) of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth lack well-defined serrations. Some teeth (including the holotype) have a wave-like double recurvature when viewed front to back, which Buffetaut and Ingavat compared to that seen in [[Carnosauria|carnosaur]] teeth from the same formation and one ''[[Deinonychus]]'' tooth described by [[John Ostrom]] in 1969. The ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype is symmetrically concave front to back, and bears 15 flutes (lengthwise ridges) on its [[Glossary of dentistry#lingual|lingual]] (the side that faces the tongue) and [[Glossary of dentistry#labial|labial]] (outward facing) surfaces. These flutes run from the base of the crown before stopping {{Convert|5|mm|}} from the rounded tooth tip. A region of the holotype where the [[Tooth enamel|enamel]] (outer layer of the teeth) has weathered away reveals that these flutes extend down to the [[Dentin|dentine]] (second layer of the teeth).<ref name=\":0\" /> The enamel also has a granular (finely wrinkled) texture, as seen in teeth from ''Baryonyx''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2007|title=The spinosaurid dinosaur Baryonyx (Saurischia, Theropoda) in the Early Cretaceous of Portugal|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/geological-magazine/article/spinosaurid-dinosaur-baryonyx-saurischia-theropoda-in-the-early-cretaceous-of-portugal/E2F9B7C099506CE2CD948E022FBDAD5E|journal=Geological Magazine|language=en|volume=144|issue=6|pages=1021\u20131025|doi=10.1017/S0016756807003883|bibcode=2007GeoM..144.1021B|issn=1469-5081|via=}}</ref> Some of the [[Tooth root|root]] is preserved in the holotype and, as in all theropods, there is a large pocket for the tooth [[Pulp (tooth)|pulp]], which would have housed blood vessels and nerves. The holotype is among the larger teeth discovered by Buffetaut and Ingavat, one much smaller specimen (DMR TF 2043b) measures {{Convert|24.3|mm|}} in length. According to the authors, this dramatic size range suggests the teeth are from individuals of different ages.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Possible material ===\n[[File:Siamosaurus.jpg|thumb|Speculative [[Paleoart|restoration]] of ''Siamosaurus'' based on relatives]]\n\nThe first Sebayashi Formation specimen (GMNH-PV-999) is an isolated tooth crown with a partially intact root. It is unknown on which jaw the tooth was positioned nor which surface faced the inside or outside of the mouth. The tooth's front and back carinae are well-defined, though the former is not well preserved. Besides having a broader, {{Convert|20 by 14|mm||adj=on}} wide base and being slightly smaller at {{Convert|51|mm|}} in length, GMNH-PV-999 has a very similar morphology to the ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype. Features shared between the two specimens include: a straight and only slightly compressed shape; a somewhat oval cross section; no serrations on the carinae (possibly due to bad preservation); and a flutes on the crown surface, the Japan specimen having 12 on each side. The specimens also share a crown surface with numerous small granular structures oriented parallel to their lengths. Because of these resemblances, Hasegawa and colleagues regarded GMNH-PV-999 as nearly identical to DMR TF 2043a.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n[[File:Sebayashi_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Partial tooth of an indeterminate spinosaurid (KDC-PV-0003) and possible ''Siamosaurus'' tooth (GMNH-PV-999), in the [[National Museum of Nature and Science]], Tokyo]]\n\nKDC-PV-0003, the second tooth found in the Sebayashi Formation, consists of a slightly recurved crown fragment with a preserved length of {{Convert|10|mm|}}. At its base, the crown is {{Convert|7.4|mm|}} long and {{Convert|6.8|mm|}} wide, with an almost circular cross section. Though less complete than the former specimens, KDC-PV-0003 exhibits better preservation of small details such as visible serrations, although poorly defined ones. The denticles, of which there are two to three every {{Convert|1|mm||adj=on}}, are visible only on the front carinae, due to the rear of the tooth being obscured by rock [[Matrix (geology)|matrix]]. A {{Convert|5.5|mm||adj=on}} long gap at the fossil's base exposes the dentine, which is covered in a {{Convert|1.6|mm||adj=on}} thick layer of enamel. The little that is preserved of KDC-PV-0003 shows that like the first Sebayashi Formation tooth, it has a granular texture and a minimum of 12 flutes on its surface, not all of which stretch to the full length of the crown. The granular structures of KDC-PV-0003 are sharper than in GMNH-PV-999. The interdenticle sulci (tiny furrows near the gaps between each denticle) of KDC-PV-0003 have an [[Oblique angle|oblique]] orientation of 45 degrees, exactly like those seen in GMNH-PV-999.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOut of the four teeth referred to ''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'', specimen [[IVPP]] V 4793 is the most intact, although still somewhat deformed. The crown, which is missing its tip, is {{Convert|69|mm|}} long and {{Convert|16.5 by 13|mm|}} wide at the base. The tooth is straight, only slightly recurved, and has an oval cross section. The front and rear carinae are distinct, though their serrations have been heavily eroded, similar to those of KDC-PV-0003. Like the Thailand and Japan teeth, the ''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'' specimens bear developed flutes and a granular surface. As in both Sebayashi Formation teeth, there are 12 flutes on each face of ''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis''{{'}}s teeth. Like in KDC-PV-0003, thee flutes of varied lengths. Buffetaut and colleagues likened them most to those of ''Siamosaurus'', with respect to their identical crown shape, fluting, and granular enamel.<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />\n\n== Classification ==\n[[File:Spinosaurus_sp_Marocco_Cenom.JPG|thumb|Tooth of the related genus ''[[Spinosaurus]]'', Museo di Storia Naturale A. Stoppani, [[Lombardy]]]]\n\nIn 1986, Buffetaut and Ingavat classified ''Siamosaurus'' as a theropod because of the straight tall crown and double lateral recurvature of its teeth. At the time, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s particular combination of dental characteristics, especially the longitudinal fluting and lack of serrations, had not been observed in other theropods. The authors noted similarities in ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth to those of [[Ceratosauria|ceratosaurian]] tooth crowns, some of which also have longitudinal flutes. However, this identification was ruled out, since ceratosaur teeth differ in cross section, bear far fewer dental flutes, and have distinct serrations. Buffetaut and Suteethorn concluded that the closest taxon in dentition to ''Siamosaurus'' was ''Spinosaurus''. Like ''Siamosaurus,'' this African genus had straight and unserrated conical teeth, and though ''Spinosaurus'' lacked the developed flutes seen in ''Siamosaurus,'' Buffetaut and Ingavat noted that both smooth and fluted spinosaur teeth have been reported from Africa. Therefore, they tentatively placed ''Siamosaurus'' in the Spinosauridae [[Family (biology)|family]], based on close similarities in dentition to ''Spinosaurus aegyptiacus.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nMany palaeontologists have expressed skepticism towards Buffetaut and Ingavat's identification of ''Siamosaurus'', given that spinosaurid teeth, including many from Asia, have been time and again mistaken for those of aquatic reptiles like crocodilians, plesiosaurs, and ichthyosaurs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2010-01-01|title=Spinosaurs before Stromer: early finds of spinosaurid dinosaurs and their interpretations|url=http://sp.lyellcollection.org/content/343/1/175|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|language=en|volume=343|issue=1|pages=175\u2013188|bibcode=2010GSLSP.343..175B|doi=10.1144/SP343.10|issn=0305-8719}}</ref> In view of this, the German palaeontologist [[Hans-Dieter Sues]] and colleagues in 2002 argued that there is not enough material to confidently identify ''Siamosaurus'' as a dinosaur.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sues|first=Hans-Dieter|last2=Frey|first2=Eberhard|last3=Martill|first3=David M.|last4=Scott|first4=Diane M.|date=2002-09-19|title=Irritator challengeri, a spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Brazil|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|language=en|volume=22|issue=3|pages=535\u2013547|doi=10.1671/0272-4634(2002)022[0535:icasdt]2.0.co;2|issn=0272-4634}}</ref> In 2004, American palaeontologist [[Thomas Holtz]] and colleagues considered it a [[nomen dubium|''nomen dubium'']] (dubious name), stating that its teeth might instead belong to contemporaneous fish such as [[saurodontid]] or [[Ichthyodectidae|ichthyodectid]] [[Teleost|teleosts]].<ref name=\"HMC04\">Holtz Jr., T.R., Molnar, R.E., and Currie, P.J. (2004). \"Basal Tetanurae\". In: Weishampel, D.B., Dodson, P., and Osm\u00f3lska, H. (eds.), ''The Dinosauria'' (second edition). Berkeley: University of California Press:Berkeley, p. 71-110. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}</ref> The same year, American palaeontologist [[David Weishampel]] and colleagues placed ''Siamosaurus'' as an indeterminate theropod.<ref>{{Citation|last=Weishampel|first=David|title=Dinosaur Distribution|date=2004-06-12|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/234025996|pages=517\u2013606|access-date=2018-08-28|last2=Le Loeuff|first2=Jean|last3=Coria|first3=Rodolfo|last4=M. P. Gomani|first4=Elizabeth|last5=Zhao|first5=X|last6=Xu|first6=Xing|last7=Barrett|first7=Paul|last8=Sahni|first8=Ashok|last9=Noto|first9=Christopher}}</ref> And in 2012, an analysis by American palaeontologist Matthew Carrano and colleagues agreed with the possibility of confusion with other reptiles, and regarded the genus as a possible indeterminate spinosaur. They pointed out that oftentimes, isolated teeth are an unstable foundation for naming theropod taxa, and most species based on them turn out to be invalid.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Carrano|first=Matthew T.|last2=Benson|first2=Roger B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=Scott D.|date=2012-05-17|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|language=en|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927|issn=1477-2019}}</ref> This problem is especially common with spinosaurs, given that [[Cranium|cranial]] and skeletal fossils from the group are rare.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite journal|last=William Elliott HONE|first=David|last2=Richard HOLTZ|first2=Thomas|date=2017-06-01|title=A Century of Spinosaurs - A Review and Revision of the Spinosauridae with Comments on Their Ecology|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/318228524|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica - English Edition|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Plesiosaur_skull.jpg|thumb|left|Spinosaurid teeth are often mistaken for those of [[plesiosaurs]] (above) and vice versa, though there are certain differences between their dentition]]\n\nSome crocodilians have teeth with flutes similar to those in Asian spinosaurid teeth. However, crocodilian teeth are usually more strongly recurved than spinosaur teeth.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Crocodilians also lack the lateral double recurvature of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s tooth crowns, which, based on their shape, were probably vertically inserted into the jaw, whereas long-snouted crocodilian teeth are usually jut out from the mouth at an angle. Though ''Siamosaurus'' and plesiosaur teeth are similar in overall shape, Buffetaut and Ingavat point out that plesiosaurs have significantly more-recurved tooth crowns.<ref name=\":0\" /> Compared to plesiosaurs, Asian spinosaurid teeth also have coarser and more numerous flutes that extend almost the whole length of the crown.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />''<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2008, Buffetaut and colleagues noted that \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' teeth bear carinae on the plane of the crown's curvature, a condition not observed in plesiosaur teeth. The discovery of the Khok Kruat skeleton and of baryonychine teeth with dental flutes similar to those of ''Siamosaurus'', were also brought up by the researchers as further evidence of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s spinosaurid classification.''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />'' Later discoveries revealed that flutes and a lack of serrations were common characteristics of spinosaurid teeth.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Schultz|first2=Cesar L.|date=2017-11-06|title=Spinosaur taxonomy and evolution of craniodental features: Evidence from Brazil|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=12|issue=11|pages=e0187070|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187070|issn=1932-6203|pmc=5673194|pmid=29107966|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1287070S}}</ref><ref name=\":16\" /> \n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek.jpg|thumb|Restoration of ''[[Ichthyovenator]]'', a [[Spinosaurinae|spinosaurine]] from what is now Laos]]\n\nIn 2017, the Brazilian palaeontologists Marcos Sales and Cesar Schultz accepted ''Siamosaurus'' as a spinosaur, but stated that its teeth and those of ''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'' are too similar to those of other Cretaceous spinosaurids to unequivocally erect new taxa.<ref name=\":17\" /> However, Carrano and colleagues stated that the Khok Kruat skeleton may provide answers to their identification.<ref name=\":6\" /> Authors such as Milner and colleagues,<ref name=\":9\" /> Bertin Tor,<ref name=\":14\" /> Kamonlak Wongko and colleagues,<ref name=\":8\" /> and Thomas Holtz<ref name=\"Holtz2008\">{{cite book|title=Dinosaurs: The Most Complete, Up-to-Date Encyclopedia for Dinosaur Lovers of All Ages|last=Holtz|first=Thomas R. Jr.|date=2011|chapter=Winter 2010 Appendix|chapter-url=http://www.geol.umd.edu/~tholtz/dinoappendix/HoltzappendixWinter2010.pdf}}</ref> regarded the skeleton as first irrefutable evidence of spinosaurs in Asia. Nevertheless, in 2012 Ronan Allain and colleagues described the Laos spinosaurid ''[[Ichthyovenator]]'' and dubbed it \"The first definitive Asian spinosaurid\".<ref name=\"AXRK12\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref> Mickey Mortimer pointed out shortly after that even discounting teeth, the Khok Kruat skeleton was first mentioned eight years prior to ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s description.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dml.cmnh.org/2012Apr/msg00480.html|title=RE: Ichthyovenator, new spinosaurid from Early Cretaceous of Laos|website=dml.cmnh.org|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref> Sales and Shultz suggested that the various Asian teeth might eventually be attributed to ''Ichthyovenator''-like forms.<ref name=\":17\" /> In a 2014 abstract, Allain announced that three teeth from ''Ichthyovenator'' had been discovered, which typically of spinosaurines, bore straight and unserrated crowns. Though no comparison was made to the other Asian teeth.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Allain|first=Ronan|date=2014|title=New material of the theropod Ichthyovenator from Ban Kalum type locality (Laos): Implications for the synonymy of Spinosaurus and Sigilmassasaurus and the phylogeny of Spinosauridae|url=http://vertpaleo.org/GlobalPDFS/SVP-2014-Program-and-Abstract-Book-9-18-2014.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology Programs and Abstracts|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nSpinosaurids were large [[Bipedalism|bipedal]] [[Carnivore|carnivores]] with well-built forelimbs and elongated, crocodile-like skulls. The [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] and [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] affinities of the group are subject to active research and debate, given that in comparison to other theropod groups, many of the family's taxa are based on poor fossil material.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Traditionally, the group is split into the [[subfamilies]] Spinosaurinae (unserrated, straight teeth with well marked flutes and a circular cross section) and Baryonychinae (finely serrated, somewhat recurved teeth with weaker flutes and a more oval cross section). The morphological variation seen in spinosaurid teeth, however, shows that these characteristics are not always consistent within the subfamilies.<ref name=\":19\" /> The exact position of ''Siamosaurus'' within the Spinosauridae is difficulty to determine because of its fragmentary nature, problems in classifying the many Asian spinosaur teeth stem from the lack of associated skulls or skeletons.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002-09-01|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409}}</ref> Asian spinosaurid teeth show characteristics from both Spinosaurinae and Baryonychinae, such as how KDC-PV-0003 shares irregularly sized mesial serrations with the latter group.<ref name=\":5\" /> In 2010, the British palaeontologist David Hone and colleagues referred ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' to the Spinosaurinae.<ref name=\":19\" /> Likewise, British palaeontologist Thomas Arden and colleagues resolved ''Siamosaurus'' as a basal member of the Spinosaurinae in 2019, their [[cladogram]] can be seen below.<ref name=\"arden2018\">{{cite journal|last=Arden|first=T.M.S.|last2=Klein|first2=C.G.|last3=Zouhri|first3=S.|last4=Longrich|first4=N.R.|date=|year=2019|title=Aquatic adaptation in the skull of carnivorous dinosaurs (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) and the evolution of aquatic habits in ''Spinosaurus''|url=|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=93|pages=275\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2018.06.013|via=}}</ref>\n\n{{clade|{{clade\n |1=Praia das Aguncheiras taxon\n |label2=[[Baryonychinae]]\n |2={{clade\n  |1=''[[Baryonyx walkeri]]'' [[File:Baryonyx_walkeri_restoration.jpg|middle|80px]]\n  |2=''[[Suchomimus tenerensis]]'' [[File:Suchomimustenerensis_(Flipped).png|middle|80px]] }}\n |label3=[[Spinosaurinae]]\n |3={{clade\n  |1='''''Siamosaurus suteethorni'''''\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=Eumeralla taxon\n   |2={{clade\n    |1=''[[Ichthyovenator laosensis]]'' [[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek_(Flipped).jpg|middle|77px]]\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Irritator challengeri]]'' [[File:Irritator Life Reconstruction.jpg|middle|80 px]]\n     |2=''[[Oxalaia quilombensis]]''\n     |label3=[[Spinosaurini]]\n     |3={{clade\n      |1=Gara Samani taxon\n      |2=''[[Sigilmassasaurus brevicollis]]''\n      |3=''[[Spinosaurus aegyptiacus]]'' [[File:Spinosaurus by Joschua Kn\u00fcppe.png|middle|80 px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}|style=font-size: 85%; line-height:85%;|label1=[[Spinosauridae]]}}\n\n==Palaeobiology==\n\n=== Diet and feeding ===\nBuffetaut and Ingavat suggested in 1986 that ''Siamosaurus'', like other spinosaurids, probably led a heavily [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) lifestyle. Spinosaurids had highly specialised teeth better suited for piercing rather than tearing flesh, thanks to their long, conical tooth crowns with reduced or absent serrations. This dental morphology is also seen in plesiosaurs and long-snouted crocodilians.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\">{{Cite journal|last=Hone|first=David William Elliott|last2=Holtz|first2=Thomas Richard|date=June 2017|title=A century of spinosaurs \u2013 a review and revision of the Spinosauridae with comments on their ecology|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica \u2013 English Edition|language=en|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328|issn=1000-9515}}</ref> Though skull material from ''Siamosaurus'' is lacking, spinosaurs are known to have had low, narrow and elongated jaws with snout tips that fanned out into a [[Rosette (design)|rosette]]-like shape, similar to that of modern [[Gharial]]<nowiki/>s.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Fossil evidence shows that besides fish, spinosaurids also consumed pterosaurs and other dinosaurs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Martill|first2=David|last3=Escuilli\u00e9|first3=Fran\u00e7ois|date=2004-07-01|title=Pterosaurs as part of a spinosaur diet|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/430033a|journal=Nature|language=En|volume=429|issue=6995|pages=33|doi=10.1038/430033a|pmid=15229562|bibcode=2004Natur.429...33B|issn=0028-0836}}</ref> In the Sao Khua Formation, localities such as Wat Sakawan have yielded sauropod remains in association with tooth crowns from ''Siamosaurus'', documenting either predation or scavenging on part of the latter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n[[File:Spinosaurid_and_Kinnareemimus.PNG|thumb|Restoration of a generic spinosaur feeding on a [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] carcass in the [[Sao Khua Formation]] (''[[Kinnareemimus]]'' in the background), based on teeth belonging to ''Siamosaurus''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Lacerda|first2=Marcel B.|last3=Horn|first3=Bruno L. D.|last4=Oliveira|first4=Isabel A. P. de|last5=Schultz|first5=Cesar L.|date=2016-02-01|title=The \"\u03c7\" of the Matter: Testing the Relationship between Paleoenvironments and Three Theropod Clades|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=11|issue=2|pages=e0147031|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147031|pmid=26829315|pmc=4734717|issn=1932-6203|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147031S}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2006, Thai biologist Komsorn Lauprasert examined fossils collected from the Phu Kradung, Sao Khua, and Khok Kruat Formations. In this study, the teeth of ''Siamosaurus'' and a Morrocan spinosaurid were compared to those of crocodilians using [[Scanning electron microscope|scanning electron microscopy]]. Lauprasert found that spinosaurids and crocodilians may have employed similar feeding tactics and been under comparable [[Constraint (classical mechanics)|mechanical constraints]], based on resemblances in the [[microstructure]] of their tooth enamel. Lauprasert suggested that ''Siamosaurus'' could have therefore replaced the [[ecological niche]] of contemporaneous long-snouted crocodilians as a piscivorous predator. He notes that this likely occured in correlation with the rising aridity of the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations during the Early Cretaceous, since ''Siamosaurus'' had better mobility in a dry environment than crocodilians did. This could explain the absence of long-snouted crocodilian fossils from that time and place.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite thesis|last=Lauprasert|first=Komsorn|title=Evolution and palaeoecology of crocodiles in the mesozoic of Khorat plateau, Thailand|date=2006|publisher=Chulalongkorn University|url=https://cuir.car.chula.ac.th/handle/123456789/14411|language=en}}</ref> A similar scenario was proposed for spinosaurids by Hone and colleagues in 2010, who noted that, compared to large crocodilians and obligate aquatic predators, they could more easily travel from one body of water to another in search for prey.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n=== Aquatic habits ===\n\nA 2010 publication by French palaeontologist Romain Amiot and colleagues found that the [[isotopes of oxygen|oxygen isotope]] ratios of spinosaurid bones indicated [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles. Isotope ratios of spinosaurid teeth from various localities, including Thailand and China, were compared with isotopic compositions from contemporaneous theropods, turtles, and crocodilians. The study revealed that, among theropods, spinosaurid isotope ratios were closer to those of turtles and crocodilians. Thai spinosaurid teeth tended to have the largest difference from the ratios of other theropods, and those from Morocco tended to have the least difference. The authors concluded that spinosaurids, like modern crocodilians and hippopotamuses, spent much of their daily lives in or near water. They also suggested that semiaquatic habits and piscivory may explain how spinosaurids coexisted with other large theropods; by feeding on different prey items and occupying a distinct ecological niche, the different types of theropods would have been out of direct competition.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\"RMetal10\">{{cite journal |last=Amiot |first=R. |author2=Buffetaut, E. |author3=L\u00e9cuyer, C. |author4=Wang, X. |author5=Boudad, L. |author6=Ding, Z. |author7=Fourel, F. |author8=Hutt, S. |author9=Martineau, F. |author10=Medeiros, A. |author11=Mo, J. |author12=Simon, L. |author13=Suteethorn, V. |author14=Sweetman, S. |author15=Tong, H. |author16=Zhang, F. |author17=Zhou, Z. |year=2010 |title=Oxygen isotope evidence for semi-aquatic habits among spinosaurid theropods |journal=Geology |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=139\u2013142 |doi=10.1130/G30402.1|bibcode=2010Geo....38..139A }}</ref>\n\n== Palaeoenvironment and palaeobiogeography ==\n[[File:Sao_Khua_Formation_V2.png|thumb|left|Restoration of ''Siamosaurus'' hunting fish in the Sao Khua Formation, with a herd of ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]]'' in the background]]\n\nThe sediments of the Sao Khua Formation, composed of [[Red clay|red clays]], [[Mudstone|mudstones]], [[Sandstone|sandstones]], [[Siltstone|siltstones]] and [[Conglomerate (geology)|conglomerate]] rocks, record a [[fluvial]] environment dominated by lakes, [[Floodplain|floodplains]], and meandering low-energy rivers.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> This is consistent with the types of vertebrate fauna present in the formation, which comprise only terrestrial or freshwater animals, including dinosaurs, turtles, freshwater [[hybodont sharks]] and [[Actinopterygii|actinopterygian]] fishes, and the freshwater crocodilian ''[[Sunosuchus]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> Besides ''Siamosaurus'', there were dinosaurs like the [[Metriacanthosauridae|metriacanthosaurid]] ''Siamotyrannus isanensis'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carrano|first1=M. T.|last2=Benson|first2=R. B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=S. D.|date=2012|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927}}</ref> the [[Ornithomimosauria|ornithomimosaur]] ''[[Kinnareemimus]] khonkaenensis'',<ref name=\"description\">Buffetaut, E., Suteethorn, V. and Tong, H. (2009). \"An early 'ostrich dinosaur' (Theropoda: Ornithomimosauria) from the Early Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of NE Thailand\", pp. 229-243 IN E. Buffetaut, G. Cuny, J. Le Loeuff & V. Suteethorn (eds.), ''Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Ecosystems in SE Asia''. Geological Society, London, Special Publications 315: 229-243. {{doi|10.1144/SP315.16}}</ref> the [[Megaraptora|megaraptoran]] ''[[Phuwiangvenator]]'' ''yaemniyomi'', the basal [[Coelurosauria|coelurosaur]] ''[[Vayuraptor]]'' ''nongbualamphuensis,<ref name=\"Samathietal2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=A.|last2=Chanthasit|first2=P.|last3=Martin Sander|first3=P.|date=May 2019|title=Two new basal coelurosaurian theropod dinosaurs from the Lower Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of Thailand|journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica|language=en|volume=64|issue=2|pages=239\u2013260|doi=10.4202/app.00540.2018}}</ref>'' a ''[[Compsognathus]]''-like theropod, as well as sauropods like ''Phuwiangosaurus sirindhornae'' and two indeterminate forms. Sauropod remains are some of the most abundant in the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> No [[Ornithischia|ornithischian]] dinosaur fossils have been found in the Sao Khua Formation, possibly suggesting that they were uncommon compared to [[Saurischia|saurischian]] dinosaurs.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations had a more [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] climate than the older, more humid [[Phu Kradung Formation]].<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe Khok Kruat Formation is composed mostly of sandstones, conglomerates, siltstones, and [[Shale|shales]]. Similarly to the Sao Khua Formation, the deposition of these sediments occurred in an arid to semi-arid floodplain environment of slow-moving, meandering rivers.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=Jintasakul|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|last4=You|first4=Hai-Lu|date=2015-12-30|title=A New Basal Hadrosauroid Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation in Nakhon Ratchasima Province, Northeastern Thailand|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=10|issue=12|pages=e0145904|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0145904|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4696827|pmid=26716981|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1045904S}}</ref> Vertebrates from the Khok Kruat assemblage include [[Semionotiformes|semionotiform]] fishes, hybodont sharks, turtles, dinosaurs, pterosaurs, and crocodilians. The dinosaur fauna of this ecosystem included the [[Carcharodontosauridae|carcharodontosaurid]] ''[[Siamraptor]]'' ''suwati'',''<ref name=\"Chokchaloemwong2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Chokchaloemwong|first=Duangsuda|last2=Hattori|first2=Soki|last3=Cuesta|first3=Elena|last4=Jintasakul|first4=Pratueng|last5=Shibata|first5=Masateru|last6=Azuma|first6=Yoichi|date=2019-10-09|editor-last=Liu|editor-first=Jun|title=A new carcharodontosaurian theropod (Dinosauria: Saurischia) from the Lower Cretaceous of Thailand|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=14|issue=10|pages=e0222489|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0222489|pmid=31596853|pmc=6784982|issn=1932-6203}}</ref>'' [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontians]] like ''[[Sirindhorna]] khoratensis'',<ref name=\":15\" /> ''[[Ratchasimasaurus]] suranaerae'',<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=JINTASAKUL|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|date=2011-10-01|title=A New Iguanodontian Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation, Nakhon Ratchasima in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/264655916|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica|volume=85|issue=5|pages=969\u2013976|doi=10.1111/j.1755-6724.2011.00530.x}}</ref> and ''[[Siamodon]] nimngami'';<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2011-01-01|title=A new iguanodontian dinosaur from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous, Aptian) of northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396911000425|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|language=en|volume=97|issue=1\u20132|pages=51\u201362|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2011.08.001|issn=0753-3969|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh}}</ref> as well as a ''Phuwiangosaurus''-like sauropod,<ref name=\":7\" /> an indeterminate [[Ceratopsia|ceratopsian]],<ref name=\"sereno2010\">{{cite book|title=New Perspectives on Horned Dinosaurs: The Royal Tyrrell Museum Ceratopsian Symposium|last=Sereno|first=Paul C.|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2010|editor1-last=Ryan|editor1-first=Michael J.|location=Bloomington and Indianapolis|pages=21\u201358|chapter=Taxonomy, cranial morphology, and relationships of parrot-beaked dinosaurs (Ceratopsia:''Psittacosaurus'')|editor2-last=Chinnery-Allgeier|editor2-first=Brenda J.|editor3-last=Eberth|editor3-first=David A.}}</ref> and various indeterminate theropods.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> The formation is probably equivalent to the [[Gres superieurs Formation]] of Laos, since animals like advanced iguanodontians, sauropods, and spinosaurids have also been found there.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\nIn 2010, American palaeontologist [[Stephen L. Brusatte|Stephen Brusatte]] and colleagues noted that the discovery of spinosaurids in Asia, a family previously known only from Europe, Africa, and South America, suggests faunal interchange between the [[Supercontinent|supercontinents]] [[Laurasia]] (in the north) and [[Gondwana]] (in the south) during the early Late Cretaceous. Though it may also be possible that spinosaurids already had a [[cosmopolitan distribution]] before the Middle Cretaceous, and thus preceding the breakup of Laurasia from Gondwana. However, the authors noted that more evidence is needed to test this hypothesis.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Brusatte|first=Stephen|last2=B. J. Benson|first2=R|last3=Xu|first3=Xing|date=2010-12-10|title=The evolution of large-bodied therood dinosaurs during the Mesozoic in Asia|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260714806|journal=Journal of Iberian Geology|volume=36|issue=2|pages=275\u2013296|doi=10.5209/rev_JIGE.2010.v36.n2.12}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n{{Megalosauroidea}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q134636}}\n\n[[Category:Spinosaurids]]\n[[Category:Barremian life]]\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1986]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by \u00c9ric Buffetaut]]\n", "name_user": "PaleoGeekSquared", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siamosaurus"}
